{"title_page": "Conyers-Rockdale Library System", "text_new": "{{Infobox library\n| name               = Conyers-Rockdale Library System\n| name_en            = <!-- Name in English if different -->\n| logo               = [[File:Conyers-Rockdale_Library_System.png|300px]]\n| logo_size          = \n| logo_alt           = \n| image              = <!-- file name only (no Image: or File:) -->\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| country            = \n| type               = \n| scope              = \n| established        = 1919\n| dissolved          = \n| ref_legal_mandate  = \n| location           = Conyers, Georgia\n| coordinates        = \n| branch_of          = \n| num_branches       = 1\n| items_collected    = \n| collection_size    = 107,469 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib2016\" />\n| criteria           = \n| legal_deposit      = \n| req_to_access      = \n| annual_circulation = 243,025 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib2016\" />\n| pop_served         = 90,489 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib2016\" />\n| members            = 43,234 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib2016\">{{cite web|title=Current Look at Georgia Libraries 2016|url=http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-16.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045215/http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-16.pdf|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| budget             = \n| director           = Brenda Poku<ref>{{cite news |title=Brenda Poku named library director of Conyers-Rockdale Library |url=https://cviog.uga.edu/news/071818-poku.html |accessdate=9 October 2018 |work=cviog.uga.edu |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=news@rockdalecitizen.com |first1=By Staff Report |title=Nancy Guinn hires new director |url=https://www.rockdalenewtoncitizen.com/news/local/nancy-guinn-hires-new-director/article_fbc63d69-2cf4-5d19-8138-4326db68bc9b.html |accessdate=9 October 2018 |work=Rockdale Citizen & Newton Citizen |language=en}}</ref>\n| num_employees      = \n| website            = http://conyersrockdalelibrary.org\n| references         = \n| embed              = \n| module             = \n}}\n{{Coord|33.664869|-84.018142|display=title}}\nThe '''Conyers-Rockdale Library System (CRLS)''' is a [[public library]] located in [[Rockdale County, Georgia]]. It is home to one branch on Green Street, [[Conyers, Georgia]], the Nancy Guinn Memorial Library.\n\nCRLS is a member of [[Public Information Network for Electronic Services|PINES]], a program of the [[Georgia Public Library Service]] that covers 53 library systems in 143 counties of Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|title=PINES - About|url=http://pines.georgialibraries.org/about|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref> Any resident in a PINES supported library system has access to over 10.6 million books in the system's circulation.<ref>{{cite web|title=PINES Facts|url=http://pines.georgialibraries.org/sites/default/files/files/PINES_Facts_2016.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref> The library is also serviced by GALILEO, a program of the University System of Georgia which stands for \"GeorgiA LIbrary LEarning Online\". This program offers residents in supported libraries access to over 100 databases indexing thousands of periodicals and scholarly journals. It also boasts over 10,000 journal titles in full text.<ref>{{cite web|title=GALILEO - About|url=http://about.galileo.usg.edu/|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Library History===\nThe first iteration of a library in Rockdale County was established by the Conyers Civic League out of the Conyers Public School in 1919. The school, recently rebuilt in 1915 due to a fire, required a library to meet new Georgia accreditation.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=CRLS History|url=http://conyersrockdalelibrary.org/?page_id=217|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe library officially changed its name to Nancy Guinn Memorial Library in 1921. Nancy Guinn was the founder and president of the Conyers Civic League which worked to construct the library originally, and helped establish a committee to bring in more volumes to the growing library.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nIn 1953 the library became part of the DeKalb Regional Library System, a three-county regional library system including Newton, DeKalb and Rockdale counties. These libraries worked in relation with each other until 1989 when all three libraries decided to disband and form their own library systems in their respective counties.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Short History of the Library (Newtown County Library System)|url=http://www.newtonlibrary.org/about-your-library/short-history-library|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===The Blade Sculpture===\nThe current logo of the library features a 25 foot abstract painted steel and fiberglass sculpture known as \"The Blade\". The Blade sits on current library property and was commissioned in 1971 to a new up-and-coming sculptor named [[James Clover]]. It was built as a symbol \"In honor of all members of the Conyers Civic League, past, present and future.\"<ref name=\"History\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reports|first1=Staff|title=Library Showcases New Logo|journal=The Citizens|date=January 14, 2013|url=http://www.rockdalenewtoncitizen.com/news/library-showcases-new-logo/article_0d8d047f-7306-5b21-8fe1-326861fb430f.html|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Blade is included in the database of the Inventories of American Painting and Sculpture of the Smithsonian American Art Museum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!434050~!0#focus|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Library systems in neighboring counties==\n*[[Gwinnett County Public Library]] to the north.\n*[[Azalea Regional Library System]] to the north east.\n*[[Newton County Library System]] to the south east.\n*[[Henry County Library System]] to the south west.\n*[[DeKalb County Public Library]] to the north west.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://gapines.org/eg/opac/ PINES Catalog]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:County library systems in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox library\n| name               = Conyers-Rockdale Library System\n| name_en            = <!-- Name in English if different -->\n| logo               = [[File:Conyers-Rockdale_Library_System.png|300px]]\n| logo_size          = \n| logo_alt           = \n| image              = <!-- file name only (no Image: or File:) -->\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| country            = \n| type               = \n| scope              = \n| established        = 1919\n| dissolved          = \n| ref_legal_mandate  = \n| location           = Conyers, Georgia\n| coordinates        = \n| branch_of          = \n| num_branches       = 1\n| items_collected    = \n| collection_size    = 107,469 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib2016\" />\n| criteria           = \n| legal_deposit      = \n| req_to_access      = \n| annual_circulation = 243,025 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib2016\" />\n| pop_served         = 90,489 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib2016\" />\n| members            = 43,234 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib2016\">{{cite web|title=Current Look at Georgia Libraries 2016|url=http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-16.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045215/http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-16.pdf|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| budget             = \n| director           = Brenda Poku<ref>{{cite news |title=Brenda Poku named library director of Conyers-Rockdale Library |url=https://cviog.uga.edu/news/071818-poku.html |accessdate=9 October 2018 |work=cviog.uga.edu |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=news@rockdalecitizen.com |first1=By Staff Report |title=Nancy Guinn hires new director |url=https://www.rockdalenewtoncitizen.com/news/local/nancy-guinn-hires-new-director/article_fbc63d69-2cf4-5d19-8138-4326db68bc9b.html |accessdate=9 October 2018 |work=Rockdale Citizen & Newton Citizen |language=en}}</ref>\n| num_employees      = \n| website            = http://conyersrockdalelibrary.org\n| references         = \n| embed              = \n| module             = \n}}\n{{Coord|33.664869|-84.018142|display=title}}\nThe '''Conyers-Rockdale Library System (CRLS)''' is a [[public library]] located in [[Rockdale County, Georgia]]. It is home to one branch on Green Street, [[Conyers, Georgia]], the Nancy Guinn Memorial Library.\n\nCRLS is a member of [[Public Information Network for Electronic Services|PINES]], a program of the [[Georgia Public Library Service]] that covers 53 library systems in 143 counties of Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|title=PINES - About|url=http://pines.georgialibraries.org/about|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref> Any resident in a PINES supported library system has access to over 10.6 million books in the system's circulation.<ref>{{cite web|title=PINES Facts|url=http://pines.georgialibraries.org/sites/default/files/files/PINES_Facts_2016.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref> The library is also serviced by GALILEO, a program of the University System of Georgia which stands for \"GeorgiA LIbrary LEarning Online\". This program offers residents in supported libraries access to over 100 databases indexing thousands of periodicals and scholarly journals. It also boasts over 10,000 journal titles in full text.<ref>{{cite web|title=GALILEO - About|url=http://about.galileo.usg.edu/|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Library History===\nThe first iteration of a library in Rockdale County was established by the Conyers Civic League out of the Conyers Public School in 1919. The school, recently rebuilt in 1915 due to a fire, required a library to meet new Georgia accreditation.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=CRLS History|url=http://conyersrockdalelibrary.org/?page_id=217|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe library officially changed its name to Nancy Guinn Memorial Library in 1921. Nancy Guinn was the founder and president of the Conyers Civic League which worked to construct the library originally, and helped establish a committee to bring in more volumes to the growing library.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nIn 1953 the library became part of the DeKalb Regional Library System, a three-county regional library system including Newton, DeKalb and Rockdale counties. These libraries worked in relation with each other until 1989 when all three libraries decided to disband and form their own library systems in their respective counties.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Short History of the Library (Newtown County Library System)|url=http://www.newtonlibrary.org/about-your-library/short-history-library|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===The Blade Sculpture===\nThe current logo of the library features a 25 foot abstract painted steel and fiberglass sculpture known as \"The Blade\". The Blade sits on current library property and was commissioned in 1971 to a new up-and-coming sculptor named [[James Clover]]. It was built as a symbol \"In honor of all members of the Conyers Civic League, past, present and future.\"<ref name=\"History\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reports|first1=Staff|title=Library Showcases New Logo|journal=The Citizens|date=January 14, 2013|url=http://www.rockdalenewtoncitizen.com/news/library-showcases-new-logo/article_0d8d047f-7306-5b21-8fe1-326861fb430f.html|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Blade is included in the database of the Inventories of American Painting and Sculpture of the Smithsonian American Art Museum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!434050~!0#focus|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Library systems in neighboring counties==\n*[[Gwinnett County Public Library]] to the north.\n*[[Azalea Regional Library System]] to the north east.\n*[[Newton County Library System]] to the south east.\n*[[Henry County Library System]] to the south west.\n*[[DeKalb County Public Library]] to the north west.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://gapines.org/eg/opac/ PINES Catalog]\n\n[[Category:County library systems in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conyers-Rockdale_Library_System"}
{"title_page": "Converse Memorial Library", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n | name =Converse Memorial Library\n | nrhp_type = nhl\n | image = Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - angle view.JPG\n | caption = Converse Memorial Building\n | location= 36 Salem Street, [[Malden, Massachusetts]]\n | coordinates = {{coord|42|25|39|N|71|3|59|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Massachusetts#USA\n | area = {{convert|1|acre|ha}}\n | built =1885\n| architect= [[H.H. Richardson]]; Shepley, Rutan & Coolidge\n| architecture= [[Richardson Romanesque]]\n| designated_nrhp_type=December 23, 1987<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1899&ResourceType=Building|title=Converse Memorial Library|accessdate=2008-07-07|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606042254/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1899&ResourceType=Building|archive-date=2009-06-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n | added = September 05, 1985<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=85002014\n}}\nThe '''Converse Memorial Library''' &ndash; also known as '''Converse Memorial Building''' &ndash; is a historically significant building designed by noted American architect [[Henry Hobson Richardson|H. H. Richardson]]. From 1885 to 1996, it housed the Malden Public Library, which now occupies a modern building adjacent to it. The former library is located at 36 Salem Street, [[Malden, Massachusetts]].\n\nThe building was a gift of Elisha S. and Mary D. Converse in memory of their murdered son, Frank Eugene Converse, who was the victim of the first bank robbery/murder in [[North America]]. It was constructed 1883-1885 in an overall L-shape, with a facade of brown Longmeadow [[sandstone]], a tower rising from the L's inner corner, and a heavily arched entry porch set within the L's short arm. The main library room is 50 x 36 feet and finished in elaborately carved white oak with a high, vaulted ceiling. Its furniture was designed by Richardson and manufactured by the Boston firm of [[A. H. Davenport and Company]].<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nIn 1896 two additions were made to the building, designed by Richardson's successor firm, [[Shepley, Rutan & Coolidge]].  One gable-roofed wing extends the building to the rear, along Park Street, following the same general lines of the existing structure.  The other addition was a flat-roofed rectangular stack area also attached to the rear.  An octagonal gallery space further extended the rear in 1916, designed by Newhall and Blevins.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nThe Converse Memorial Building was the last of Richardson's library designs, and is generally considered among his finest works. It was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1987.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/><ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Converse Memorial Library / Malden Public Library|url={{NHLS url|id=85002014}} |format=pdf |author=Carolyn Pitts |publisher=National Park Service}} (includes plans and drawings) and {{NHLS url|id=85002014|title=''Accompanying six photos, exterior and interior, from 1888, 1895, 1905, 1985''|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(32&nbsp;KB)}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Massachusetts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* Jeffrey Karl Ochsner, ''H. H. Richardson: Complete Architectural Works'', MIT Press, 1985, page 314. {{ISBN|0-262-65015-0}}.\n* American Library Association, ''Annual Conference Proceedings of the American Library Association'',  1889, pages 78\u201379.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090606042254/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1899&ResourceType=Building National Historic Landmarks entry]\n* [http://www.bc.edu/bc_org/avp/cas/fnart/fa267/hhr_libraries.html Digital Archive of American Architecture]\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - street view.JPG|General view from street\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - end view.JPG|End view\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - decorated facade.JPG|Facade decorations\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - tower.JPG|Tower detail\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - columns.JPG|Columns\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - detail.JPG|Detail\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - ornament.JPG|Ornament\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - American Architect & Building News.JPG|1885 illustrations of the library\n</gallery>\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Massachusetts}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1885]]\n[[Category:Richardsonian Romanesque architecture in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Henry Hobson Richardson buildings]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Libraries on the National Register of Historic Places in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Education in Malden, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Malden, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n | name =Converse Memorial Library\n | nrhp_type = nhl\n | image = Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - angle view.JPG\n | caption = Converse Memorial Building\n | location= 36 Salem Street, [[Malden, Massachusetts]]\n | coordinates = {{coord|42|25|39|N|71|3|59|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Massachusetts#USA\n | area = {{convert|1|acre|ha}}\n | built =1885\n| architect= [[H.H. Richardson]]; Shepley, Rutan & Coolidge\n| architecture= [[Richardson Romanesque]]\n| designated_nrhp_type=December 23, 1987<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1899&ResourceType=Building|title=Converse Memorial Library|accessdate=2008-07-07|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606042254/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1899&ResourceType=Building|archive-date=2009-06-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n | added = September 05, 1985<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=85002014\n}}\nThe '''Converse Memorial Library''' &ndash; also known as '''Converse Memorial Building''' &ndash; is a historically significant building designed by noted American architect [[Henry Hobson Richardson|H. H. Richardson]]. From 1885 to 1996, it housed the Malden Public Library, which now occupies a modern building adjacent to it. The former library is located at 36 Salem Street, [[Malden, Massachusetts]].\n\nThe building was a gift of Elisha S. and Mary D. Converse in memory of their murdered son, Frank Eugene Converse, who was the victim of the first bank robbery/murder in [[North America]]. It was constructed 1883-1885 in an overall L-shape, with a facade of brown Longmeadow [[sandstone]], a tower rising from the L's inner corner, and a heavily arched entry porch set within the L's short arm. The main library room is 50 x 36 feet and finished in elaborately carved white oak with a high, vaulted ceiling. Its furniture was designed by Richardson and manufactured by the Boston firm of [[A. H. Davenport and Company]].<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nIn 1896 two additions were made to the building, designed by Richardson's successor firm, [[Shepley, Rutan & Coolidge]].  One gable-roofed wing extends the building to the rear, along Park Street, following the same general lines of the existing structure.  The other addition was a flat-roofed rectangular stack area also attached to the rear.  An octagonal gallery space further extended the rear in 1916, designed by Newhall and Blevins.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nThe Converse Memorial Building was the last of Richardson's library designs, and is generally considered among his finest works. It was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1987.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/><ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Converse Memorial Library / Malden Public Library|url={{NHLS url|id=85002014}} |format=pdf |author=Carolyn Pitts |publisher=National Park Service}} (includes plans and drawings) and {{NHLS url|id=85002014|title=''Accompanying six photos, exterior and interior, from 1888, 1895, 1905, 1985''|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(32&nbsp;KB)}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Massachusetts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* Jeffrey Karl Ochsner, ''H. H. Richardson: Complete Architectural Works'', MIT Press, 1985, page 314. {{ISBN|0-262-65015-0}}.\n* American Library Association, ''Annual Conference Proceedings of the American Library Association'',  1889, pages 78\u201379.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090606042254/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1899&ResourceType=Building National Historic Landmarks entry]\n* [http://www.bc.edu/bc_org/avp/cas/fnart/fa267/hhr_libraries.html Digital Archive of American Architecture]\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - street view.JPG|General view from street\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - end view.JPG|End view\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - decorated facade.JPG|Facade decorations\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - tower.JPG|Tower detail\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - columns.JPG|Columns\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - detail.JPG|Detail\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - ornament.JPG|Ornament\nImage:Converse Memorial Library (Malden, MA) - American Architect & Building News.JPG|1885 illustrations of the library\n</gallery>\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Massachusetts}}\n\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1885]]\n[[Category:Richardsonian Romanesque architecture in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Henry Hobson Richardson buildings]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Libraries on the National Register of Historic Places in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Education in Malden, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Malden, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Converse_Memorial_Library"}
{"title_page": "Paul Fireman", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Fireman\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = February 14, 1944\n| birth_place        = Cambridge, MA\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| alma_mater         = \n| employer           = Fireman Capital Partners\n| occupation         = Businessman and Humanitarian\n| residence          = \n| networth           = {{gain}} US$1.1 [[1,000,000,000|billion]] (August 2018)<ref name=ForbesBillionaires>[https://www.forbes.com/profile/paul-fireman/?list=billionaires The World's Billionaires: \"Paul Fireman\"], Forbes.com; accessed June 11, 2016.</ref>\n| spouse             = Phyllis<ref name=rynecki/>\n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Fireman''' is an [[United States|American]] businessman and humanitarian, who for 26 years led [[Reebok|Reebok International, Ltd]]. as Chairman and CEO to become one of the most popular athletic shoe companies worldwide. Beyond financial success, he is well known as a business visionary and a champion for human rights. Fireman challenged corporate America to become more socially responsible and demonstrated that all corporations could succeed financially, while simultaneously serving the public good. He sold Reebok to Adidas in 2006, but his life and business ventures continue to reflect his philanthropy in serving people and communities throughout the country today. \n\n==Early Life and Education==\nFireman was born February 14, 1944 in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]] to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref name=rynecki>{{cite news|last1=Rynecki|first1=David|title=FIREMAN'S FANTASY|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2005/10/17/8358052/index.htm|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=Fortune|date=17 October 2005}}</ref> and raised in the working-class city of [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], also called 'Shoe City'. Fireman grew up with an insatiable love for golf and as a 10-year-old, caddied at [[Thorny Lea Golf Club]] in his hometown. He viewed golf as \u201ca code of conduct, a way of life, and a tremendous character builder.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertynationalgc.com/club/scripts/library/view_document.asp?NS=PUBLIC&DN=HISTORY|title=Liberty National\u00a0Club History|website=www.libertynationalgc.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> He attended high school at [[Tabor Academy (Massachusetts)|Tabor Academy]], a private secondary school in Marion, MA and matriculated to where he attended [[Boston University]], but did not graduate.<ref name=lat>{{cite news|last1=AP|title=The Man Who Made Reebok Jump High|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/aug/15/business/fi-reebok15|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=LA Times|date=15 August 2005}}</ref> \n\n==Personal Life==\n\nPaul Fireman and his wife Phyllis<ref name=\"lat\" /> (n\u00e9e Brenner) grew up in [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton, MA]] and met at age 12 at a YMCA mixer. Paul states it was love at first sight and said, \u201cI knew the minute I met her it was my destiny\u201d (Interview with Paul Fireman April 2020). They were married in May 1964 and have three grown children and nine grandchildren. \n\nFireman and his wife, Phyllis, are competitive bridge players. In 2014, his team won the Roth Open Swiss Teams at the Summer North American Bridge Championship (NABC) in Las Vegas<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/massachusetts/newton/chestnut-hill-native-wins-national-title-north-american-bridge-championship|title=Chestnut Hill native wins national title at North American Bridge Championship|date=2014-08-19|website=Newton, MA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and subsequently captured the bronze medal representing the U.S. in Chennai, India at the World Bridge Championships in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldbridge.org/competitions/wbf-championships/world-bridge-teams-championships/the-bermuda-bowl/|title=The Bermuda Bowl {{!}} World Bridge Federation|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\nFireman began his career at age 18 working in the family business, Boston Camping, selling outdoor sporting goods and fishing tackle for 15 years.<ref name=\"lat\" /> After starting in the warehouse, he moved his way up through the business eventually running it with his brother. As the family business declined, Fireman sought new opportunities. \n\nWhile attending a sporting goods show in Chicago in 1979 Fireman met Joe Foster, the owner of a British running shoe company founded in 1895 called Reebok.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/reebok-cofounder-shares-3-rules-for-startup-success-2017-4|title=Reebok co-founder shares 3 rules for startup success|last=Johnson|first=Kieron|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Fireman acquired the North American sales rights to [[Reebok]] in 1979 and eventually bought the British-based parent company outright in 1984.<ref name=\"lat\" /><ref name=\"healy\" /> Reebok capitalized on the increasing popularity of aerobics in California and introduced the world\u2019s first aerobic shoe designed specifically for women in 1982 called Freestyle. Riding the success of the Freestyle shoe as the aerobics craze swept across America, Fireman grew the company and Reebok issued an [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] in 1985.<ref name=\"lat\" /> In 1986, Reebok surpassed Nike as the top-selling manufacturer of athletic shoes in the United States, second only in the world to Adidas. Starting in 1986, Reebok acquired several companies to create a multinational corporation, including Avia, a rival athletic shoemaker; John A. Frye, the prestigious and stylish boot maker; Rockport, a company known for its sporting and casual shoes; and Ellesse, an Italian company known for making expensive athletic shoes and clothing. Later acquisitions included Boston Whaler and The Hockey Company (CCM)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/reebok-to-buy-ccm-jofa-koho-brands-in-329-million-us-takeover-1.474982|title=Reebok to buy CCM, Jofa, Koho brands in $329 million US takeover|last=|first=|date=April 8, 2004|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Starting in 2000 Reebok signed multiyear, exclusive licensing deals with the NFL<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/20/sports/pro-football-reebok-strikes-exclusive-deal-with-nfl.html|title=PRO FOOTBALL; Reebok Strikes Exclusive Deal With N.F.L.|date=2000-12-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, NBA<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reporter|first=a Wall Street Journal Staff|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB996707098368148995|title=Reebok Reaches Deal With NBA To Become Its Exclusive Outfitter|date=2001-08-02|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>, and NHL<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/09/15/reebok-nhl-adidas/|title=Reebok passes the NHL puck to Adidas|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. \n\nDuring his tenure at Reebok, Fireman challenged corporate America to become more socially responsible and proved that corporations can financially succeed while serving the public good. He worked diligently to improve human rights worldwide. In 1986, Reebok became one of the first companies to pull out of South Africa because of the country's practice of apartheid and two years later Reebok sponsored the Amnesty International Human Rights Now tour. Fireman subsequently established the annual Reebok Human Rights Awards in 1988 recognizing activists under the age of 30 who exposed and reduced human rights atrocities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fireman|first=Paul|title=From the Pain Come the Dream: The Recipients of the Reebok Human Rights Award|publisher=Umbrage|year=2003|isbn=1884167357|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>\n\nFireman sold Reebok to [[Adidas]] in 2005.<ref name=\"healy\">{{cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Beth|title=Paul Fireman takes another shot|url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/06/10/reebok_founder_fireman_returns_to_sneaker_business_with_20m_stake_in_colorado_firm/|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=The Boston Globe|date=10 June 2011}}</ref> He is currently the Chairman of Fireman Capital Partners, a Boston-based, consumer-focused private equity firm founded in 2008 by Paul Fireman and his son Dan, the firm\u2019s Managing Partner.<ref name=\"healy\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firemancapital.com/team/dan-fireman/|title=Dan Fireman {{!}} Fireman Capital Partners {{!}} Boston Massachusetts|website=www.firemancapital.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==Golf Course Development==\n\nFireman has been active in golf course development and in 1991 he purchased Willowbend Country Club ([[Mashpee, Massachusetts|Mashpee, MA]]). The development of additional courses followed that included Rio Mar Resort and Country Club ([[Puerto Rico]]), Costa Caribe Golf and Country Club (Puerto Rico), Coco Beach Golf and Country Club (Puerto Rico), The Ranch Golf Club ([[Southwick, Massachusetts|Southwick, MA]]), and Starr Pass Club ([[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson, AZ]]).<ref name=\"rynecki\" />\n \n[[Liberty National Golf Club]] ([[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City, NJ]]) is Fireman\u2019s most impressive foray in to the world of golf. In 1995 Fireman purchased a mile of neglected and decaying New Jersey shoreline along the Hudson River that was an eyesore. The land the Liberty National lies upon has a unique and storied history including an ammunition depot during World War I, and a prisoner of war camp during World War II, and more recently as an oil refinery and warehouse for industrial goods. However, the land when Fireman originally toured the site was \u201ca toxic moonscape of corroded oil tanks, contaminated soil, and rusting warehouses.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/07/24/golf-barclays-pga-lifestyle-sports-golf-liberty-national.html|title=Inside A $250 Million Golf Course|last=Bertoni|first=Steven|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \u201cI loved the site and the historical value with the Statue of Liberty, and the city, and it was on the water,\u201d Fireman says. \u201cI just plunged into it because I thought it would be a phenomenal golf site and improve the world. And I was just crazy enough to do it.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertynationalgc.com/club/scripts/library/view_document.asp?NS=PUBLIC&DN=HISTORY|title=Liberty National\u00a0Club History|website=www.libertynationalgc.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> At Fireman\u2019s expense, the toxic land was cleaned to remove all residual debris, capped, and covered with 6 million cubic feet of soil that was brought in by truck to create the course.\n\nSince its opening in 2006, Liberty National has hosted three [[FedEx Cup]] playoff tournaments ([[The Barclays]] in 2009, 2013 and [[The Northern Trust]] in 2019) and [[Presidents Cup|the Presidents Cup]] in 2017. Liberty National also hosts junior golf tournaments, the First Tee of New Jersey, and local high school golf teams from Jersey City practice and play their home matches at the course.  \n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nThe Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation was created in 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=www.ppffound.org/about/|title=The Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Since its inception, the foundation has distributed over $165 million to charitable organizations with a focus primarily on improving the communities of both Massachusetts and New Jersey.\n\nAddressing homelessness has been a major initiative of the foundation. One Family Inc. was created to preventing family homelessness through advocacy, education, and innovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=www.onefamilyinc.org|title=One Family, Inc.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Using a multi-pronged approach, One Family advocates for public policies that will increase affordable housing and provide services to families experiencing or who are at risk for homelessness with an aim to promote permanent solutions to homelessness. The Paul and Phyllis Fireman Foundation also joined with other donors to create Home Funders, a collaborative fund that finances very affordable rental housing for low-income families in Massachusetts.\n\nFireman is a strong supporter of [[The First Tee]] whose mission is to impact the lives of young people by providing educational programs that build character, instill life-enhancing values and promote healthy habits through the game of golf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/The_First_Tee/Fireman_Donation/prweb12989117.htm|title=Paul and Dan Fireman Show Support For The First Tee Chapters of New Jersey With a Unique Donation|website=PRWeb|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.hunter-pr.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/TFT-NJ-Mentees.pdf|title=Paul Fireman Meets Mentees from New Jersey First Tee Chapters|date=May 12, 2016|work=Hunter Public Relations|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith the COVID-19 pandemic sweeping through the United States, the Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation rapidly acted in March 2020 by making impactful donations to the Massachusetts COVID-19 Relief Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macovid19relieffund.org/|title=Massachusetts COVID-19 Relief Fund|website=www.macovid19relieffund.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, the Boston Resiliency Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/treasury/boston-resiliency-fund|title=Boston Resiliency Fund|date=2020-03-16|website=Boston.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, the Jersey City COVID-19 Response Fund, and the New Jersey Pandemic Relief Fund. \n\n===Campaign contributions===\nFireman donated $250,000 to Republican [[Mitt Romney]]'s 2012 presidential campaign, but Fireman has also donated to Democratic Senators [[Bob Menendez]] and [[Cory Booker]] and several other candidate and committees of both parties.<ref name=auditor>{{cite news|title=Man who wants to build Jersey City casino is a big political donor: The Auditor|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/07/man_who_wants_to_build_jersey_city_casino_is_a_big_political_donor_the_auditor.html|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=NJ.com|date=14 July 2014}}</ref> Fireman donated $1 million to the 2016 presidential campaign of New Jersey Governor [[Chris Christie]].<ref name=friedman>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Matt|title=Billionaires, casino interests give to Christie super PAC|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/chris-christie-super-pac-donors-120864|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=Politico|date=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Firemen was an important backer of Public Question 1, a ballot measure that would amend New Jersey's constitution to allow casino Gambling in North Jersey.<ref name=\"Fire\">[http://blogs.northjersey.com/meadowlands-matters/backers-of-meadowlands-jersey-city-casinos-suspend-campaign-1.1665185?platform=hootsuite]</ref> After numerous polls showed that Question 1 had no chance to pass Fireman, along with Jeff Gural, pulled their financial support for the measure. Bill Cortese, the leader of Trenton's Bad Bet, a group opposed to the question, said, \"Trenton's Bad Bet will not be distracted by billionaire developers throwing temper tantrums because they don't get what they want.\"<ref name=\"Bad\">[http://bigstory.ap.org/article/23514f35c8f642e8b87a38e4c909020b/campaign-pushing-expand-gambling-new-jersey-suspended]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fireman, Paul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Fireman\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = February 14, 1944\n| birth_place        = Cambridge, MA\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| alma_mater         = \n| employer           = Fireman Capital Partners\n| occupation         = Businessman and Humanitarian\n| residence          = \n| networth           = {{gain}} US$1.1 [[1,000,000,000|billion]] (August 2018)<ref name=ForbesBillionaires>[https://www.forbes.com/profile/paul-fireman/?list=billionaires The World's Billionaires: \"Paul Fireman\"], Forbes.com; accessed June 11, 2016.</ref>\n| spouse             = Phyllis<ref name=rynecki/>\n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Fireman''' is an [[United States|American]] businessman and humanitarian, who for 26 years led [[Reebok|Reebok International, Ltd]]. as Chairman and CEO to become one of the most popular athletic shoe companies worldwide. Beyond financial success, he is well known as a business visionary and a champion for human rights. Fireman challenged corporate America to become more socially responsible and demonstrated that all corporations could succeed financially, while simultaneously serving the public good. He sold Reebok to Adidas in 2006, but his life and business ventures continue to reflect his philanthropy in serving people and communities throughout the country today. \n\n==Early Life and Education==\nFireman was born February 14, 1944 in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]] to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref name=rynecki>{{cite news|last1=Rynecki|first1=David|title=FIREMAN'S FANTASY|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2005/10/17/8358052/index.htm|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=Fortune|date=17 October 2005}}</ref> and raised in the working-class city of [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], also called 'Shoe City'. Fireman grew up with an insatiable love for golf and as a 10-year-old, caddied at [[Thorny Lea Golf Club]] in his hometown. He viewed golf as \u201ca code of conduct, a way of life, and a tremendous character builder.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertynationalgc.com/club/scripts/library/view_document.asp?NS=PUBLIC&DN=HISTORY|title=Liberty National\u00a0Club History|website=www.libertynationalgc.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> He attended high school at [[Tabor Academy (Massachusetts)|Tabor Academy]], a private secondary school in Marion, MA and matriculated to where he attended [[Boston University]], but did not graduate.<ref name=lat>{{cite news|last1=AP|title=The Man Who Made Reebok Jump High|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/aug/15/business/fi-reebok15|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=LA Times|date=15 August 2005}}</ref> \n\n==Personal Life==\n\nPaul Fireman and his wife Phyllis<ref name=\"lat\" /> (n\u00e9e Brenner) grew up in [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton, MA]] and met at age 12 at a YMCA mixer. Paul states it was love at first sight and said, \u201cI knew the minute I met her it was my destiny\u201d (Interview with Paul Fireman April 2020). They were married in May 1964 and have three grown children and nine grandchildren. \n\nFireman and his wife, Phyllis, are competitive bridge players. In 2014, his team won the Roth Open Swiss Teams at the Summer North American Bridge Championship (NABC) in Las Vegas<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/massachusetts/newton/chestnut-hill-native-wins-national-title-north-american-bridge-championship|title=Chestnut Hill native wins national title at North American Bridge Championship|date=2014-08-19|website=Newton, MA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and subsequently captured the bronze medal representing the U.S. in Chennai, India at the World Bridge Championships in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldbridge.org/competitions/wbf-championships/world-bridge-teams-championships/the-bermuda-bowl/|title=The Bermuda Bowl {{!}} World Bridge Federation|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\nAfter working in a variety of jobs, including for a family-owned sporting goods store,<ref name=lat/> Fireman acquired the North American sales rights to [[Reebok]] in 1979.<ref name=healy/> He later bought the British-based parent company in 1984.<ref name=lat/> Capitalizing on the increasing popularity of aerobics, particularly with women, Fireman grew the company and issued an [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] in 1985.<ref name=lat/>  Fireman sold Reebok to [[Adidas]] in 2005 for $3.8 billion; Fireman himself made $800 million from the deal.<ref name=healy>{{cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Beth|title=Paul Fireman takes another shot|url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/06/10/reebok_founder_fireman_returns_to_sneaker_business_with_20m_stake_in_colorado_firm/|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=The Boston Globe|date=10 June 2011}}</ref> In 2009, Fireman founded Fireman Capital Partners, an investment firm.<ref name=healy/> Fireman Capital has bought major stakes in [[Newton Running]], Hudson Jeans, and [[Evolution Fresh]].<ref name=healy/>\n\n==Golf Course Development==\n\nFireman has been active in golf course development and in 1991 he purchased Willowbend Country Club ([[Mashpee, Massachusetts|Mashpee, MA]]). The development of additional courses followed that included Rio Mar Resort and Country Club ([[Puerto Rico]]), Costa Caribe Golf and Country Club (Puerto Rico), Coco Beach Golf and Country Club (Puerto Rico), The Ranch Golf Club ([[Southwick, Massachusetts|Southwick, MA]]), and Starr Pass Club ([[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson, AZ]]).<ref name=\"rynecki\" />\n \n[[Liberty National Golf Club]] ([[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City, NJ]]) is Fireman\u2019s most impressive foray in to the world of golf. In 1995 Fireman purchased a mile of neglected and decaying New Jersey shoreline along the Hudson River that was an eyesore. The land the Liberty National lies upon has a unique and storied history including an ammunition depot during World War I, and a prisoner of war camp during World War II, and more recently as an oil refinery and warehouse for industrial goods. However, the land when Fireman originally toured the site was \u201ca toxic moonscape of corroded oil tanks, contaminated soil, and rusting warehouses.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/07/24/golf-barclays-pga-lifestyle-sports-golf-liberty-national.html|title=Inside A $250 Million Golf Course|last=Bertoni|first=Steven|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \u201cI loved the site and the historical value with the Statue of Liberty, and the city, and it was on the water,\u201d Fireman says. \u201cI just plunged into it because I thought it would be a phenomenal golf site and improve the world. And I was just crazy enough to do it.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertynationalgc.com/club/scripts/library/view_document.asp?NS=PUBLIC&DN=HISTORY|title=Liberty National\u00a0Club History|website=www.libertynationalgc.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> At Fireman\u2019s expense, the toxic land was cleaned to remove all residual debris, capped, and covered with 6 million cubic feet of soil that was brought in by truck to create the course.\n\nSince its opening in 2006, Liberty National has hosted three [[FedEx Cup]] playoff tournaments ([[The Barclays]] in 2009, 2013 and [[The Northern Trust]] in 2019) and [[Presidents Cup|the Presidents Cup]] in 2017. Liberty National also hosts junior golf tournaments, the First Tee of New Jersey, and local high school golf teams from Jersey City practice and play their home matches at the course.  \n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nThe Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation was created in 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=www.ppffound.org/about/|title=The Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Since its inception, the foundation has distributed over $165 million to charitable organizations with a focus primarily on improving the communities of both Massachusetts and New Jersey.\n\nAddressing homelessness has been a major initiative of the foundation. One Family Inc. was created to preventing family homelessness through advocacy, education, and innovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=www.onefamilyinc.org|title=One Family, Inc.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Using a multi-pronged approach, One Family advocates for public policies that will increase affordable housing and provide services to families experiencing or who are at risk for homelessness with an aim to promote permanent solutions to homelessness. The Paul and Phyllis Fireman Foundation also joined with other donors to create Home Funders, a collaborative fund that finances very affordable rental housing for low-income families in Massachusetts.\n\nFireman is a strong supporter of [[The First Tee]] whose mission is to impact the lives of young people by providing educational programs that build character, instill life-enhancing values and promote healthy habits through the game of golf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/The_First_Tee/Fireman_Donation/prweb12989117.htm|title=Paul and Dan Fireman Show Support For The First Tee Chapters of New Jersey With a Unique Donation|website=PRWeb|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.hunter-pr.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/TFT-NJ-Mentees.pdf|title=Paul Fireman Meets Mentees from New Jersey First Tee Chapters|date=May 12, 2016|work=Hunter Public Relations|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith the COVID-19 pandemic sweeping through the United States, the Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation rapidly acted in March 2020 by making impactful donations to the Massachusetts COVID-19 Relief Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macovid19relieffund.org/|title=Massachusetts COVID-19 Relief Fund|website=www.macovid19relieffund.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, the Boston Resiliency Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/treasury/boston-resiliency-fund|title=Boston Resiliency Fund|date=2020-03-16|website=Boston.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, the Jersey City COVID-19 Response Fund, and the New Jersey Pandemic Relief Fund. \n\n===Campaign contributions===\nFireman donated $250,000 to Republican [[Mitt Romney]]'s 2012 presidential campaign, but Fireman has also donated to Democratic Senators [[Bob Menendez]] and [[Cory Booker]] and several other candidate and committees of both parties.<ref name=auditor>{{cite news|title=Man who wants to build Jersey City casino is a big political donor: The Auditor|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/07/man_who_wants_to_build_jersey_city_casino_is_a_big_political_donor_the_auditor.html|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=NJ.com|date=14 July 2014}}</ref> Fireman donated $1 million to the 2016 presidential campaign of New Jersey Governor [[Chris Christie]].<ref name=friedman>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Matt|title=Billionaires, casino interests give to Christie super PAC|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/chris-christie-super-pac-donors-120864|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=Politico|date=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Firemen was an important backer of Public Question 1, a ballot measure that would amend New Jersey's constitution to allow casino Gambling in North Jersey.<ref name=\"Fire\">[http://blogs.northjersey.com/meadowlands-matters/backers-of-meadowlands-jersey-city-casinos-suspend-campaign-1.1665185?platform=hootsuite]</ref> After numerous polls showed that Question 1 had no chance to pass Fireman, along with Jeff Gural, pulled their financial support for the measure. Bill Cortese, the leader of Trenton's Bad Bet, a group opposed to the question, said, \"Trenton's Bad Bet will not be distracted by billionaire developers throwing temper tantrums because they don't get what they want.\"<ref name=\"Bad\">[http://bigstory.ap.org/article/23514f35c8f642e8b87a38e4c909020b/campaign-pushing-expand-gambling-new-jersey-suspended]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fireman, Paul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "A111861538968R", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated the career of Paul Fireman to be more accurate and current", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Fireman"}
{"title_page": "Concord Free Public Library", "text_new": "{{short description|Public library in Concord, Massachusetts}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name       = Concord Free Public Library\n| image               = Concord free public library.jpg\n| caption             = Interior of the library, 1873\n| map_type            = \n| altitude            = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]]\n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| ren_cost            =\n| location            = Concord, Massachusetts\n| address             = 129 Main St., Concord, Mass. 01742 <ref name=\"cfpl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.concordlibrary.org/|title=Concord Free Public Library|date=2009-01-10|work=Concord Free Public Library|publisher=Concord Free Public Library}}</ref>\n| client              = \n| owner               = \n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|42.458|-71.353}}\n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = 1873\n| inauguration_date   =\n| renovation_date     = 1889, 1917, Early 1930s, 1938, 1968, 1986 to 1990, 2003 to 2005 <ref name=\"historic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.concordlibrary.org/scollect/BuildingHistories/CFPL/index.html|title=Concord Historic Buildings|date=2009-01-10|work=Concord Free Public Library|publisher=Concord Free Public Library|access-date=2009-01-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007222207/http://www.concordlibrary.org/scollect/BuildingHistories/CFPL/index.html|archive-date=2008-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| demolition_date     = \n| destruction_date    = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = 3\n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| architecture_firm   = Snell and Gregerson\n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| ren_architect       =\n| ren_firm            =\n| ren_str_engineer    = \n| ren_serv_engineer   = \n| ren_civ_engineer    = \n| ren_oth_designers   = \n| ren_qty_surveyor    = \n| ren_awards          = \n| references          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Concord Free Public Library''' is a public library in the town of [[Concord, Massachusetts]]. The main building is located at 129 Main Street, and the Fowler branch is located at 1322 Main Street in West Concord.\n\n==History==\nThe Concord Free Public Library was founded by Concord native William Munroe, son of the [[William Munroe (pencil maker)|famed pencil-maker]]. Munroe worked with other prominent members of Concord to form a Board of Trustees that would provide financial backing for the library.  Building plans were commissioned by [[Boston]] firm [[Snell and Gregerson]]. The land was purchased in 1869, and construction began in 1872. The library was dedicated on October 1, 1873.\n\nIn March 1885, the Concord Free Library was the first institution to ban Mark Twain's ''[[The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn]]'', and a number of New England newspapers applauded their condemnation:  the ''Daily Advertiser'' (Boston), the ''Daily Republican'' (Springfield, MA), and the ''Freeman'' (Concord, MA).  But many criticized or mocked the library's decision, and as a number of contemporaries and Twain himself noted, the ban contributed to the novel's publicity and helped its sales.<ref>Michael Patrick Hearn, \"Introduction,\" ''The Annotated Huckleberry Finn'' (New York & London: W.W. Norton, 2001), pp. lxxvi-lxxxii.</ref>\n\nThe Fowler branch of the Concord Free Public Library, designed by architect [[Harry Little (architect)|Harry Little]], was dedicated on May 18, 1930.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Public libraries in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Concord, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1873]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Concord, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public library in Concord, Massachusetts}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name       = Concord Free Public Library\n| image               = Concord free public library.jpg\n| caption             = Interior of the library, 1873\n| map_type            = \n| altitude            = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]]\n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| ren_cost            =\n| location            = Concord, Massachusetts\n| address             = 129 Main St., Concord, Mass. 01742 <ref name=\"cfpl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.concordlibrary.org/|title=Concord Free Public Library|date=2009-01-10|work=Concord Free Public Library|publisher=Concord Free Public Library}}</ref>\n| client              = \n| owner               = \n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|42.458|-71.353}}\n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = 1873\n| inauguration_date   =\n| renovation_date     = 1889, 1917, Early 1930s, 1938, 1968, 1986 to 1990, 2003 to 2005 <ref name=\"historic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.concordlibrary.org/scollect/BuildingHistories/CFPL/index.html|title=Concord Historic Buildings|date=2009-01-10|work=Concord Free Public Library|publisher=Concord Free Public Library|access-date=2009-01-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007222207/http://www.concordlibrary.org/scollect/BuildingHistories/CFPL/index.html|archive-date=2008-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| demolition_date     = \n| destruction_date    = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = 3\n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| architecture_firm   = Snell and Gregerson\n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| ren_architect       =\n| ren_firm            =\n| ren_str_engineer    = \n| ren_serv_engineer   = \n| ren_civ_engineer    = \n| ren_oth_designers   = \n| ren_qty_surveyor    = \n| ren_awards          = \n| references          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Concord Free Public Library''' is a public library in the town of [[Concord, Massachusetts]]. The main building is located at 129 Main Street, and the Fowler branch is located at 1322 Main Street in West Concord.\n\n==History==\nThe Concord Free Public Library was founded by Concord native William Munroe, son of the [[William Munroe (pencil maker)|famed pencil-maker]]. Munroe worked with other prominent members of Concord to form a Board of Trustees that would provide financial backing for the library.  Building plans were commissioned by [[Boston]] firm [[Snell and Gregerson]]. The land was purchased in 1869, and construction began in 1872. The library was dedicated on October 1, 1873.\n\nIn March 1885, the Concord Free Library was the first institution to ban Mark Twain's ''[[The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn]]'', and a number of New England newspapers applauded their condemnation:  the ''Daily Advertiser'' (Boston), the ''Daily Republican'' (Springfield, MA), and the ''Freeman'' (Concord, MA).  But many criticized or mocked the library's decision, and as a number of contemporaries and Twain himself noted, the ban contributed to the novel's publicity and helped its sales.<ref>Michael Patrick Hearn, \"Introduction,\" ''The Annotated Huckleberry Finn'' (New York & London: W.W. Norton, 2001), pp. lxxvi-lxxxii.</ref>\n\nThe Fowler branch of the Concord Free Public Library, designed by architect [[Harry Little (architect)|Harry Little]], was dedicated on May 18, 1930.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Public libraries in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Concord, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1873]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Concord, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concord_Free_Public_Library"}
{"title_page": "Dark-sky movement", "text_new": "The '''dark-sky movement''' is a [[social movement|campaign]] to reduce [[light pollution]]. The advantages of reducing light pollution include an increased number of stars visible at night, reducing the effects of electric lighting on the environment, improving the well-being,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Summers|first=J. K.|last2=Smith|first2=L. M.|last3=Case|first3=J. L.|last4=Linthurst|first4=R. A.|date=June 2012|title=A Review of the Elements of Human Well-Being with an Emphasis on the Contribution of Ecosystem Services|journal=Ambio|volume=41|issue=4|pages=327\u2013340|doi=10.1007/s13280-012-0256-7|issn=0044-7447|pmc=3393065|pmid=22581385}}</ref> health<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chepesiuk|first=Ron|date=January 2009|title=Missing the Dark: Health Effects of Light Pollution|journal=Environmental Health Perspectives|volume=117|issue=1|pages=A20\u2013A27|issn=0091-6765|pmc=2627884|pmid=19165374|doi=10.1289/ehp.117-a20}}</ref> and safety<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.darksky.org/light-pollution/lighting-crime-and-safety/|title=Lighting, Crime and Safety|last=|first=|date=|website=www.darksky.org}}</ref> of both people and wildlife,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2003/04/0417_030417_tvlightpollution.html|title=Light Pollution Taking Toll on Wildlife, Eco-Groups Say|last=|first=|date=|website=news.nationalgeographic.com}}</ref> and cutting down on energy usage. [[Earth Hour]] and [[National Dark-Sky Week]] are two examples of such efforts.\n\nThe [[social movement|movement]] started with professional and amateur [[astronomer]]s alarmed that nocturnal [[skyglow]] from urban areas was blotting out the sight of stars. For example, the world-famous [[Palomar Observatory]] in California is threatened by sky-glow from the nearby city of [[Escondido, California|Escondido]] and local businesses.<ref>[http://www.astro.caltech.edu/palomar/community/lightpollution.html Caltech Astronomy Department]</ref> For similar reasons, astronomers in Arizona helped push the governor there to veto a bill in 2012 which would have lifted a ban on illuminated billboards.<ref>[http://azdailysun.com/news/state-and-regional/astronomers-celebrate-veto-of-billboard-bill/article_e5f59f64-3a22-5881-8015-4babce8253b2.html AZ Daily Sun: \"Astronomers celebrate veto of billboard bill\"]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[Nocturnal]] animals can be harmed by light pollution because they are biologically evolved to be dependent on an environment with a certain number of hours of uninterrupted daytime and nighttime. The [[over-illumination]] of the night sky is affecting these organisms (especially birds). This biological study of darkness is called [[scotobiology]].<ref>http://isebindia.com/05_08/05-01-3.html International society of environmental botanists: \"Scotobiology \u2013 The biology of darkness\"</ref> Light pollution has also been found to affect human circadian rhythms.<ref>http://www.darksky.org/about-ida International Dark Sky Association: About the IDA</ref>\n\nThe dark-sky movement encourages the use of [[Light pollution#Improving lighting fixtures|full-cutoff fixtures]] that cast little or no light upward in public areas and generally to encourage communities to adopt lighting regulations. A 2011 project is to establish \"dark sky oasis\" in suburban areas.<ref>[http://www.universetoday.com/91721/a-refreshing-idea-vote-for-enabling-city-kids-to-see-starry-skies/ Universe Today] IDA Suburban Outreach Sites</ref>\n\n== Dark-sky lighting ==\nDark-sky lighting is a concept very important to the dark-sky movement, as it greatly minimizes light pollution. The concept was started in the 1950s by the city of [[Flagstaff, Arizona|Flagstaff]], Arizona.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flagstaffdarkskies.org/international-dark-sky-city/flagstaffs-battle-for-dark-skies/|title=Flagstaff's Battle for Dark Skies - Flagstaff Dark Skies Coalition|last=|first=|date=|website=www.flagstaffdarkskies.org}}</ref> Flagstaff is a city of over 70,000, but because of their lighting, their skies are dark enough to see the Milky Way.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.coloradoan.com/story/news/2016/09/27/save-our-stars-city-seeks-preserve-night-skies/90970492/|title=Save our stars: City seeks to preserve night skies in Fort Collins|last=|first=|date=|work=Coloradoan}}</ref> Lights should be shielded on the top and sides so light doesn't go up to the sky and only used when needed (use motion detectors and only the wattage necessary).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.darksky.org/lighting/lighting-basics/|title=Outdoor Lighting Basics|website=www.darksky.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-05}}</ref> The [http://www.darksky.org/ International Dark-Sky Association] certifies fixtures as dark sky friendly, and these will have the [http://www.darksky.org/fsa/ IDA Fixture Seal of Approval]. Opinions vary on what color the light should be, but most agree on the description of \"warm\", which is considered more yellow or orange/amber than white.\n\n== Skyglow ==\n{{main|Skyglow}}\n[[File:M\u00e9xico City at Night 2005.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Mexico City]] at night, showing skyglow bright enough to read a book outside]]\nSkyglow is the illumination of the [[night sky]] or parts of it, resembling an orange \"[[smog]]\". It occurs from both natural and human-made sources.<ref name=cat>http://www.lrc.rpi.edu/programs/nlpip/lightinganswers/lightpollution/skyGlow.asp Lighting Resource Centre: \"What is sky glow?\".</ref> Artificial skyglow is caused by the [[over-illumination]] of the sky from large city centres, shopping centres, or stadiums. It consists of light that is either emitted directly upward or reflected from the ground that is then scattered by dust and gas molecules in the atmosphere, producing a luminous background or light dome. These artificial skyglows cause the sky to be 5\u201310 times brighter in urban areas than a naturally dark sky that is unaffected by artificial light. Natural skyglow can come from [[Natural lighting|natural light]] sources, such as the [[sunlight|Sun]], the [[moonlight|Moon]], the [[starlight|stars]], or [[Aurora (astronomy)|aurora]]s.\n\nSome communities are becoming aware of this problem and are putting forth efforts to minimize the hazy, orange skyglow. A community in particular is the city of [[Merritt, British Columbia]]. An article published July 8, 2010 states that they are making minor changes to lighting in and around Merritt, such as the installment of down-cast lighting to commercial buildings, as part of their light pollution abatement program.<ref name=\"merrittnews.net\">http://www.merrittnews.net/article/20100708/MERRITT0101/100709954/-1/MERRITT/sky-glow-burning-out Merritt News: \"Sky glow burning out?\" author: Kaleena Loehr</ref> The benefits of this technological change include \"saving energy through better focused lights, preserving the environment by reducing excess light that may affect flora and fauna, reducing crime and increasing safety by more adequately illuminating areas, and reducing health risks.\"<ref name=\"merrittnews.net\"/>\n\n== Scotobiology ==\n{{main|Scotobiology}}\nScotobiology is the study of the role darkness plays in living organisms and shows that interrupting darkness by light pollution creates drastic effects for most organisms; changing their food gathering and feeding habits, their mating and reproduction behavior, migration behaviour (birds and insects) and social behavior.<ref name=\"sampaa.org\">http://www.sampaa.org/publications/conference-proceedings-1991-2000/sampaa-6-proceedings/light-pollution/Bidwell%202010.pdf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Approximately 30% of vertebrates and 60% of invertebrates are nocturnal, meaning that they depend on darkness. Their everyday behaviors are biologically evolved to adapt in uninterrupted darkness.<ref>Scott R. Parker, S. L. (2011). Dark Skies, Bright Minds. Sources of Knowledge Forum, (pp. 12\u201317). Ontario.</ref>\n\nHuman health is also adversely affected by the effects of light pollution. Light during night time hours has been linked to human cancers and psychological disorders.<ref name=\"sampaa.org\"/>\n\n== Dark-sky preserves ==\n{{main|Dark-sky preserve}}\nDark-sky preserves are the main contributors to the dark-sky movement. They are protected areas found mostly in national parks that have a zero light pollution policy set in by the government and controlled by the National Dark Sky Association.\n\nAs of February 6, 2012, there were 35 formally recognized dark-sky preserves in the world with Canada in the lead containing 15 preserves. These preserves are located in Nova Scotia, New Brunswick, Quebec, Ontario, Saskatchewan, Alberta, and British Columbia. Other countries that have dark-sky preserves are the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, Slovakia, Spain, United Kingdom, and the United States. A current list of designated parks is maintained by the Dark Skies Advisory Group <ref>http://www.darkskyparks.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=564 Dark Skies Advisory Group</ref> of the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN).\n\nThe parks are put in place by the Dark Sky Places program with the intention to remind us that the night sky serves just as much importance to our culture and history as our day-time sky.<ref>http://www.darksky.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=564 International Dark Sky Association: \"International Dark Sky Places</ref>\n\n== International Dark-Sky Association ==\n{{main|International Dark-Sky Association}}\nThe International Dark-Sky Association (IDA) began in 1988. A non-profit, it manages the Fixture Seal of Approval program, which offers a third-party rating system judging the \"sky-friendliness\" of lighting fixtures. In 2009, the IDA opened an office for public policy and government affairs in [[Washington, D.C.]] to inform lawmakers and lobbyists about the energy efficiency of outdoor lighting and to promote the adoption of energy-saving measures.<ref>http://www.darksky.org/about-ida International Dark Sky association: \"About the IDA\"</ref> The IDA has implemented several ''simple guidelines'' to responsible outdoor lighting along with some ''practical considerations''.\n\n* In regard to safety, one needs only the right amount of light, in the right place, at the right time. More light often means wasted light and energy.\n* Use the lowest wattage of lamp that is feasible. The maximum wattage for most commercial applications should be 250 watts of high intensity discharge lighting, but less is usually sufficient.\n* Incorporate curfews (i.e., turn lights off automatically after a certain hour when businesses close or traffic is minimal).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.darksky.org/outdoorlighting/guidance |title=Simple guidelines |accessdate=2013-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208003935/http://darksky.org/outdoorlighting/guidance |archivedate=2014-02-08 }} International Dark Sky Association: \"Simple guidelines for lighting regulations. retrieved 30 December 2013</ref>\n\n== List of groups ==\n{{Div col}}\n*[http://www.anpcen.fr ANPCEN] (France)\n* [[Astronomitaly]] (Italy)\n*[[Campaign for Dark Skies]] (UK)\n*[[Canadian Geographic]] (Canada)\n*[[Canadian Scotobiology Group]] (Canada)\n*[[CieloBuio]] (Italy)\n*[[International Dark-Sky Association]]\n*[[National Dark-Sky Week]] (United States)\n*[[Niue]]\n*[[Royal Astronomical Society of Canada]] (Canada)\n{{End div col}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Bortle dark-sky scale]]\n*[[SKYGLOW]]\n*[[Dark-sky preserve]]\n*[[Noctcaelador]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.darksky.org/ International Dark-Sky Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110718102049/https://www.mydarksky.com/ MyDarkSky \u2013 dark sky survey maps]\n*[http://bbs.keyhole.com/ubb/showthreaded.php/Cat/0/Number/587221/an/0/page/0#587221/ Outdoor Lighting Regulations and Ordinances on Google Earth]\n*[http://www.lawserver.com/dark-sky-laws Interactive map comparing U.S. dark sky laws]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111028172132/http://buzzlog.yahoo.com/buzzlog/94259 The dark sky movement \u2013 yahoo]\n*[http://www.canadiangeographic.ca/magazine/apr11/astronomy_jasper_national_park.asp Jasper National Park]\n*[http://www.darkskyparks.org/dsag/DSP%20world%20list_feb2012.pdf Dark-sky parks of the world]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.flagstaffdarkskies.org/ Flagstaff Dark Skies Coalition]\n*[https://www.globeatnight.org/ Globe at Night]\n*[http://citiesatnight.org/ Cities at Night]\n*[http://www.darkskiesawareness.org/ Dark Skies Awareness]\n*[http://darkskystudies.org/ The Consortium for Dark Sky Studies]\n\n[[Category:Environmental movements]]\n[[Category:Light pollution]]\n", "text_old": "The '''dark-sky movement''' is a [[social movement|campaign]] to reduce [[light pollution]]. The advantages of reducing light pollution include an increased number of stars visible at night, reducing the effects of electric lighting on the environment, improving the well-being,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Summers|first=J. K.|last2=Smith|first2=L. M.|last3=Case|first3=J. L.|last4=Linthurst|first4=R. A.|date=June 2012|title=A Review of the Elements of Human Well-Being with an Emphasis on the Contribution of Ecosystem Services|journal=Ambio|volume=41|issue=4|pages=327\u2013340|doi=10.1007/s13280-012-0256-7|issn=0044-7447|pmc=3393065|pmid=22581385}}</ref> health<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chepesiuk|first=Ron|date=January 2009|title=Missing the Dark: Health Effects of Light Pollution|journal=Environmental Health Perspectives|volume=117|issue=1|pages=A20\u2013A27|issn=0091-6765|pmc=2627884|pmid=19165374|doi=10.1289/ehp.117-a20}}</ref> and safety<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.darksky.org/light-pollution/lighting-crime-and-safety/|title=Lighting, Crime and Safety|last=|first=|date=|website=www.darksky.org}}</ref> of both people and wildlife,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2003/04/0417_030417_tvlightpollution.html|title=Light Pollution Taking Toll on Wildlife, Eco-Groups Say|last=|first=|date=|website=news.nationalgeographic.com}}</ref> and cutting down on energy usage. [[Earth Hour]] and [[National Dark-Sky Week]] are two examples of such efforts.\n\nThe [[social movement|movement]] started with professional and amateur [[astronomer]]s alarmed that nocturnal [[skyglow]] from urban areas was blotting out the sight of stars. For example, the world-famous [[Palomar Observatory]] in California is threatened by sky-glow from the nearby city of [[Escondido, California|Escondido]] and local businesses.<ref>[http://www.astro.caltech.edu/palomar/community/lightpollution.html Caltech Astronomy Department]</ref> For similar reasons, astronomers in Arizona helped push the governor there to veto a bill in 2012 which would have lifted a ban on illuminated billboards.<ref>[http://azdailysun.com/news/state-and-regional/astronomers-celebrate-veto-of-billboard-bill/article_e5f59f64-3a22-5881-8015-4babce8253b2.html AZ Daily Sun: \"Astronomers celebrate veto of billboard bill\"]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[Nocturnal]] animals can be harmed by light pollution because they are biologically evolved to be dependent on an environment with a certain number of hours of uninterrupted daytime and nighttime. The [[over-illumination]] of the night sky is affecting these organisms (especially birds). This biological study of darkness is called [[scotobiology]].<ref>http://isebindia.com/05_08/05-01-3.html International society of environmental botanists: \"Scotobiology \u2013 The biology of darkness\"</ref> Light pollution has also been found to affect human circadian rhythms.<ref>http://www.darksky.org/about-ida International Dark Sky Association: About the IDA</ref>\n\nThe dark-sky movement encourages the use of [[Light pollution#Improving lighting fixtures|full-cutoff fixtures]] that cast little or no light upward in public areas and generally to encourage communities to adopt lighting regulations. A 2011 project is to establish \"dark sky oasis\" in suburban areas.<ref>[http://www.universetoday.com/91721/a-refreshing-idea-vote-for-enabling-city-kids-to-see-starry-skies/ Universe Today] IDA Suburban Outreach Sites</ref>\n\n== Dark-sky lighting ==\nDark-sky lighting is a concept very important to the dark-sky movement, as it greatly minimizes light pollution. The concept got started in the 1950s by the city of [[Flagstaff, Arizona|Flagstaff]], AZ.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flagstaffdarkskies.org/international-dark-sky-city/flagstaffs-battle-for-dark-skies/|title=Flagstaff's Battle for Dark Skies - Flagstaff Dark Skies Coalition|last=|first=|date=|website=www.flagstaffdarkskies.org}}</ref> Flagstaff is a city of over 70,000, but because of their lighting, their skies are dark enough to see the Milky Way.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.coloradoan.com/story/news/2016/09/27/save-our-stars-city-seeks-preserve-night-skies/90970492/|title=Save our stars: City seeks to preserve night skies in Fort Collins|last=|first=|date=|work=Coloradoan}}</ref> Lights should be shielded on the top and sides so light doesn't go up to the sky and only used when needed (use motion detectors and only the wattage necessary).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.darksky.org/lighting/lighting-basics/|title=Outdoor Lighting Basics|website=www.darksky.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-05}}</ref> The [http://www.darksky.org/ International Dark-Sky Association] certifies fixtures as dark sky friendly, and these will have the [http://www.darksky.org/fsa/ IDA Fixture Seal of Approval]. Opinions vary on what color the light should be, but most agree on the description of \"warm\", which is considered more yellow or orange/amber than white.\n\n== Skyglow ==\n{{main|Skyglow}}\n[[File:M\u00e9xico City at Night 2005.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Mexico City]] at night, showing skyglow bright enough to read a book outside]]\nSkyglow is the illumination of the [[night sky]] or parts of it, resembling an orange \"[[smog]]\". It occurs from both natural and human-made sources.<ref name=cat>http://www.lrc.rpi.edu/programs/nlpip/lightinganswers/lightpollution/skyGlow.asp Lighting Resource Centre: \"What is sky glow?\".</ref> Artificial skyglow is caused by the [[over-illumination]] of the sky from large city centres, shopping centres, or stadiums. It consists of light that is either emitted directly upward or reflected from the ground that is then scattered by dust and gas molecules in the atmosphere, producing a luminous background or light dome. These artificial skyglows cause the sky to be 5\u201310 times brighter in urban areas than a naturally dark sky that is unaffected by artificial light. Natural skyglow can come from [[Natural lighting|natural light]] sources, such as the [[sunlight|Sun]], the [[moonlight|Moon]], the [[starlight|stars]], or [[Aurora (astronomy)|aurora]]s.\n\nSome communities are becoming aware of this problem and are putting forth efforts to minimize the hazy, orange skyglow. A community in particular is the city of [[Merritt, British Columbia]]. An article published July 8, 2010 states that they are making minor changes to lighting in and around Merritt, such as the installment of down-cast lighting to commercial buildings, as part of their light pollution abatement program.<ref name=\"merrittnews.net\">http://www.merrittnews.net/article/20100708/MERRITT0101/100709954/-1/MERRITT/sky-glow-burning-out Merritt News: \"Sky glow burning out?\" author: Kaleena Loehr</ref>\nThe benefits of this technological change include \"saving energy through better focused lights, preserving the environment by reducing excess light that may affect flora and fauna, reducing crime and increasing safety by more adequately illuminating areas, and reducing health risks.\"<ref name=\"merrittnews.net\"/>\n\n== Scotobiology ==\n{{main|Scotobiology}}\nScotobiology is the study of the role darkness plays in living organisms and shows that interrupting darkness by light pollution creates drastic effects for most organisms; changing their food gathering and feeding habits, their mating and reproduction behavior, migration behaviour (birds and insects) and social behavior.<ref name=\"sampaa.org\">http://www.sampaa.org/publications/conference-proceedings-1991-2000/sampaa-6-proceedings/light-pollution/Bidwell%202010.pdf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Approximately 30% of vertebrates and 60% of invertebrates are nocturnal, meaning that they depend on darkness. Their everyday behaviors are biologically evolved to adapt in uninterrupted darkness.<ref>Scott R. Parker, S. L. (2011). Dark Skies, Bright Minds. Sources of Knowledge Forum, (pp. 12\u201317). Ontario.</ref>\n\nHuman health is also adversely affected by the effects of light pollution. Light during night time hours has been linked to human cancers and psychological disorders.<ref name=\"sampaa.org\"/>\n\n== Dark-sky preserves ==\n{{main|Dark-sky preserve}}\nDark-sky preserves are the main contributors to the dark-sky movement. They are protected areas found mostly in national parks that have a zero light pollution policy set in by the government and controlled by the National Dark Sky Association.\n\nAs of February 6, 2012, there were 35 formally recognized dark-sky preserves in the world with Canada in the lead containing 15 preserves. These preserves are located in Nova Scotia, New Brunswick, Quebec, Ontario, Saskatchewan, Alberta, and British Columbia. Other countries that have dark-sky preserves are the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, Slovakia, Spain, United Kingdom, and the United States. A current list of designated parks is maintained by the Dark Skies Advisory Group <ref>http://www.darkskyparks.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=564 Dark Skies Advisory Group</ref> of the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN).\n\nThe parks are put in place by the Dark Sky Places program with the intention to remind us that the night sky serves just as much importance to our culture and history as our day-time sky.<ref>http://www.darksky.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=564 International Dark Sky Association: \"International Dark Sky Places</ref>\n\n== International Dark-Sky Association ==\n{{main|International Dark-Sky Association}}\nThe International Dark-Sky Association (IDA) began in 1988. A non-profit, it manages the Fixture Seal of Approval program, which offers a third-party rating system judging the \"sky-friendliness\" of lighting fixtures. In 2009, the IDA opened an office for public policy and government affairs in [[Washington, D.C.]] to inform lawmakers and lobbyists about the energy efficiency of outdoor lighting and to promote the adoption of energy-saving measures.<ref>http://www.darksky.org/about-ida International Dark Sky association: \"About the IDA\"</ref> The IDA has implemented several ''simple guidelines'' to responsible outdoor lighting along with some ''practical considerations''.\n\n* In regard to safety, one needs only the right amount of light, in the right place, at the right time. More light often means wasted light and energy.\n* Use the lowest wattage of lamp that is feasible. The maximum wattage for most commercial applications should be 250 watts of high intensity discharge lighting, but less is usually sufficient.\n* Incorporate curfews (i.e., turn lights off automatically after a certain hour when businesses close or traffic is minimal).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.darksky.org/outdoorlighting/guidance |title=Simple guidelines |accessdate=2013-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208003935/http://darksky.org/outdoorlighting/guidance |archivedate=2014-02-08 }} International Dark Sky Association: \"Simple guidelines for lighting regulations. retrieved 30 December 2013</ref>\n\n== List of groups ==\n{{Div col}}\n*[http://www.anpcen.fr ANPCEN] (France)\n* [[Astronomitaly]] (Italy)\n*[[Campaign for Dark Skies]] (UK)\n*[[Canadian Geographic]] (Canada)\n*[[Canadian Scotobiology Group]] (Canada)\n*[[CieloBuio]] (Italy)\n*[[International Dark-Sky Association]]\n*[[National Dark-Sky Week]] (United States)\n*[[Niue]]\n*[[Royal Astronomical Society of Canada]] (Canada)\n{{End div col}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Bortle dark-sky scale]]\n*[[SKYGLOW]]\n*[[Dark-sky preserve]]\n*[[Noctcaelador]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.darksky.org/ International Dark-Sky Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110718102049/https://www.mydarksky.com/ MyDarkSky \u2013 dark sky survey maps]\n*[http://bbs.keyhole.com/ubb/showthreaded.php/Cat/0/Number/587221/an/0/page/0#587221/ Outdoor Lighting Regulations and Ordinances on Google Earth]\n*[http://www.lawserver.com/dark-sky-laws Interactive map comparing U.S. dark sky laws]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111028172132/http://buzzlog.yahoo.com/buzzlog/94259 The dark sky movement \u2013 yahoo]\n*[http://www.canadiangeographic.ca/magazine/apr11/astronomy_jasper_national_park.asp Jasper National Park]\n*[http://www.darkskyparks.org/dsag/DSP%20world%20list_feb2012.pdf Dark-sky parks of the world]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.flagstaffdarkskies.org/ Flagstaff Dark Skies Coalition]\n*[https://www.globeatnight.org/ Globe at Night]\n*[http://citiesatnight.org/ Cities at Night]\n*[http://www.darkskiesawareness.org/ Dark Skies Awareness]\n*[http://darkskystudies.org/ The Consortium for Dark Sky Studies]\n\n[[Category:Environmental movements]]\n[[Category:Light pollution]]\n", "name_user": "ChromeGames923", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark-sky_movement"}
{"title_page": "Proto-Romance Language", "text_new": "'''Proto-Romance''' is the [[Comparative method|comparatively]] [[Linguistic reconstruction|reconstructed]] ancestor of all [[Romance languages|Romance Languages]]. It reflects a late variety of [[Latin]], one of the [[Italic languages|Italic Languages]] in the broader [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] family.\n\nExceptionally in the field of [[Comparative linguistics|Comparative Linguistics]], specialists in Proto-Romance have at their disposal an abundant corpus of their [[Proto-language|proto language]] in its written register- that is to say, Latin. This has however had the drawback of leading many scholars to rely excessively on the written record in lieu of reconstructing Proto-Romance proper.<ref>Dworkin (2016), p. 2</ref> \n\nAs conceived in the Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman, Proto-Romance most closely reflects Latin as spoken around the sixth century AD.<ref>Kramer (2014), p. 295</ref>\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Monophthongs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|Close]]\n|{{IPA link|i}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|u}}\n|-\n![[Near-close vowel|Near-close]]\n|[[Near-close near-front unrounded vowel|\u026a]]\n|\n|[[Near-close back rounded vowel|\u028a]]\n|-\n![[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|e}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|o}}\n|-\n![[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|\u025b}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u0254}}\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Open]]\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u00e4|a}}\n|\n|}\n\n* The open-mid vowels /\u025b, \u0254/ merge with /e, o/ in all unstressed contexts.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 73\u20136</ref><ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 78</ref>\n\n* A further reduction is observed in intertonic syllables where /i, u/ merge with /\u026a, \u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 78\u201381</ref>\n\n* Vowels are lengthened allophonically in stressed open syllables,<ref>Loporcaro (2015), pp. 25\u201330</ref> although not /\u026a/ or /\u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 69</ref>\n\n* /i, u/ become [j, w] between a consonant and following vowel. [j] then triggers [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalization]], e.g. /basi\u00e1re/ [bas\u02b2\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref>\n\n=== Diphthong ===\nOnly one diphthong can be reconstructed for Proto-Romance, namely /aw/. It can be found in both stressed and unstressed positions.<ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 84</ref> Its phonemic status is however debatable, as it could also be simply regarded as a sequence of /a/ and /u/.<ref>Xavier, p. 81</ref>\n\n=== Consonants ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Labial\n! colspan=\"2\" |Coronal\n! colspan=\"2\" |Velar\n! colspan=\"2\" |Palatal\n|-\n!Nasal\n|\n|m\n|\n|n\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Occlusive\n|p\n|b\n|t\n|d\n|k\n|g\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |j\n|-\n!Fricative\n|f\n|\u03b2\n|s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Labialized\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|k\u02b7\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Vibrant\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |r\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Lateral\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |l\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n* When palatalized /t, k, n, l/ become [ts\u02b2, c, \u0272, \u028e].<ref name=\"Xavier\" /><ref>Zampaulo (2019), pp. 50, 78, 94</ref>\n* Intervocalic [c, \u0272, \u028e] regularly [[Gemination|geminate]].<ref name=\"Xavier\">Xavier (2014), pp. 92\u2013115</ref> [ts\u02b2] does so only sporadically.<ref>Wilkin (1926), pp. 11\u201314</ref>\n*Words beginning with /sC/ undergo [[Prothesis (linguistics)|prosthesis]], e.g. /st\u00e1re/ [\u026ast\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee], unless preceded by a vowel.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 125\u20136</ref><ref>Hall (1976), p. 128</ref>\n* It is debated whether /k\u02b7/ is its own phoneme or merely an allophone of /ku/ before vowels.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 100</ref>\n* There is some evidence that /f/ could have been bilabial, but a labiodental is still more likely.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 38</ref>\n* /b, d, g/ fricativize to [\u03b2, \u00f0, \u0263] between vowels or in contact with /r/ and /l/.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 48</ref>\n* Intervocalic /di, gi/ do not occur, these having previously reduced to /j/.<ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 87</ref><ref>Xavier (2016), p. 43</ref>\n*The rhotic may have been [\u027e~r], as in Spanish or Catalan.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 113</ref>\n*Word-initial /j/ underwent fortition to [\u025f].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 84</ref>\n* /ll/ had a retroflex realization: [\u026d\u026d].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 115</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 164</ref>\n* /gn/ fricativizes to [\u0263n].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 95</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 80</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n\n=== Nouns ===\nProto-Romance nouns had three cases: [[Nominative case|nominative]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], and a combined [[Genitive case|genitive]]-[[Dative case|dative]] which was only used in reference to humans.<ref>De Dardel & Gaenge (1992), p. 104</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Class\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"2\" |f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028e\u028as\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028ei\n|m\u00e1tr\u026as''{{efn|De Dardel hesitates to posit this form, giving ''m\u00e1tre'' as a possible alternative. Likewise ''p\u00e1tr\u026as~p\u00e1tre''.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tr\u026as\n|p\u00e1tri\n|-\n!Accusative\n|f\u00e9m\u026anas\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eu''{{efn|For final -u versus -\u028as, see Xavier (2014), p. 78.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eos\n|m\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tres\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|fem\u026an\u00f3ru''{{efn|Unlike De Dardel, Hall (1976, p. 18) has -''aru'' as the feminine ending, as it was in Classical Latin. On the next page, however, he admits that the evidence for it is flimsy.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eo\n|fi\u028e\u028e\u00f3ru\n|m\u00e1tri\n|matr\u00f3ru\n|p\u00e1tri\n|patr\u00f3ru\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |woman\n| colspan=\"2\" |son\n| colspan=\"2\" |mother\n| colspan=\"2\" |father\n|}\n\nSeveral Class III nouns had inflections that differed by syllable count or stress position.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 28</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |singular\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u0254\u0301mo\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|p\u00e1stor\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|s\u0254\u0301ror\n|-\n!Accusative\n|\u0254\u0301m\u026ane\n|past\u00f3re\n|sor\u00f3re\n|-\n!Translation\n|man\n|pastor\n|sister\n|}\nA few Class II nouns were pluralized with -''a'' or ''-ora,'' these originally having been neuter in Classical Latin. Though their singular was masculine, the plural was treated as feminine.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 23\u20134, 29\u201330.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Noun''{{efn|Forms given in the accusative.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2u\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2a\n|braccu\n|bracca\n|t\u025b\u0301mp\u028as\n|t\u025b\u0301mpora\n|p\u025b\u0301kt\u028as\n|p\u025b\u0301ktora\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |egg\n| colspan=\"2\" |arm\n| colspan=\"2\" |time\n| colspan=\"2\" |chest\n|}\nThe plural was often reanalyzed as a feminine singular, resulting in gender shifts.<ref>Akire & Rosen (2010), pp. 193\u20134</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Original noun\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eu\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nu\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|-\n!Fem. variant\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eas\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nas\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |leaf\n| colspan=\"2\" |firewood\n|}\nSuch a trend had already begun in Classical Latin; for example the feminine noun ''opera'' was formed from the plural of neuter ''opus.''\n\n=== Adjectives ===\n\n==== Absolute ====\nBroadly speaking, these decline as nouns do.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Gender\n| colspan=\"2\" |feminine\n| colspan=\"2\" |masculine\n| colspan=\"2\" |either\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"2\" |bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bl\u00e1nd\u028as\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|d\u028a\u0301lk\u026as\n| rowspan=\"2\" |d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Accusative\n|bl\u00e1ndas\n|bl\u00e1ndu\n|bl\u00e1ndos\n|d\u028a\u0301lke\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|d\u028a\u0301lki\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |sweet\n|}\n\n==== Comparative ====\nWhile the original Latin ending ''-(i)or'' still existed, it was only used in a limited number of adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 32, 119-20</ref><ref>Maltby (2016), p. 340</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|m\u025b\u0301\u028e\u028eor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|p\u025b\u0301jor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |pej\u00f3res\n|m\u00e1jor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026a\u0301nor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Accusative\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3re\n|pej\u00f3re\n|maj\u00f3re\n|m\u026an\u00f3re\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3ri\n| -\n|pej\u00f3ri\n| -\n|maj\u00f3ri\n|  -\n|m\u026an\u00f3ri\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |better\n| colspan=\"2\" |worse\n| colspan=\"2\" |larger\n| colspan=\"2\" |smaller\n|}\nThe typical way to form a comparative was to add either ''pl\u00fas'' or ''m\u00e1\u026as'' (meaning 'more') to an absolute adjective, which had been done sporadically in Classical Latin as well.<ref>Maltby (2016), pp. 340\u20135.</ref>\n\n==== Superlative ====\nNo dedicated ending existed to express the superlative. A variety of alternatives were used instead, such as an intensifying adverb (m\u028a\u0301ltu, b\u025b\u0301ne, etc.) or a comparative.<ref>Bauer (2016), pp. 340, 359</ref>\n\n==== Possessive ====\n\nShown here in the feminine singular.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 122</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!\n!First person\n!Second person\n!Third person\n|-\n!singular\n|m\u025b\u0301a\n|t\u028a\u0301a\n|s\u028a\u0301a\n|-\n!plural\n|n\u0254\u0301stra\n|\u03b2\u0254\u0301stra\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|}\n\n=== Pronouns ===\n\n==== Personal ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'you', 'me', etc.<ref>De Dardel & W\u00fcest (1993), p. 43</ref><ref name=\"Hall\">Hall (1983), p. 39</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Person\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u025b\u0301o''{{efn|On the cited page, Hall has this as ''ego''. However ''eo'' is found in Hall (1976), p. 216|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |n\u00f3s\n|t\u00fa\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\u03b2\u00f3s\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301lle\n| colspan=\"2\" |\u026a\u0301lli\n|-\n!Accusative\n|m\u00e9, m\u00e9ne\n|t\u00e9, t\u00e9ne\n|\u026a\u0301llas\n|\u026a\u0301llu\n|\u026a\u0301llos\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|m\u00ed, m\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|n\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|t\u00ed, t\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|\u03b2\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|\u026all\u00e9i\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|\u026all\u00fai\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|}\n\n==== Interrogative ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'who' and 'what'.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 42\u201343</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Animacy\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Animate\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Inanimate\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| colspan=\"2\" |ku\u00ed\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u026a\u0301d\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Accusative\n|ku\u025b\u0301ne\n|ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\n\nProto Romance verbs belong to three main classes, each of which is characterized by a different [[thematic vowel]]. Their conjugations are built on three stems and involve various combinations of mood, aspect, and tense.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 47\u201350</ref> Only one chart is shown below; the rest will be explained in a separate article.\n\n==== Present indicative ====\nThis could also connote the near future.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 52\u20136</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |First person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Third person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Translation\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Class I\n|k\u00e1nto\n|kant\u00e1m\u028as\n|k\u00e1ntas\n|kant\u00e1t\u026as\n|k\u00e1ntat\n|k\u00e1ntant\n|sing\n|-\n!Class II\n|d\u0254\u0301rmo\n|dorm\u00edm\u028as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026as\n|d\u0254rm\u00edt\u026as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026at\n|d\u0254\u0301rment<br>~d\u0254\u0301rm\u028ant\n|sleep\n|-\n!Class III\n|b\u00e1tto\n|batt\u00e9m\u028as\n|b\u00e1ttes\n|batt\u00e9t\u026as\n|b\u00e1ttet\n|b\u00e1ttent\n|beat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Irregular\n|s\u028a\u0301n\n|s\u028a\u0301m\u028as\n|\u025b\u0301s\n|\u025b\u0301st\u026as~s\u025b\u0301t\u026as~s\u028a\u0301t\u026as\n|\u025b\u0301st\n|s\u028a\u0301nt\n|am/are/is\n|-\n|\u00e1jo\n|a\u03b2\u00e9m\u028as\n|\u00e1s\n|a\u03b2\u00e9t\u026as\n|\u00e1t\n|\u00e1nt~\u00e1unt\n|have/has\n|}\n\n==== Participles ====\nOf these there were only two: a present active and a preterite passive. They declined like adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 122\u20133</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Present Active\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Preterite Passive\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n|-\n!Class I\n|am\u00e1nte\n|(is) adoring\n|am\u00e1ta\n|(was) adored\n|-\n!Class II\n|fin\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) finishing\n|fin\u00edta\n|(was) finished\n|-\n!Class III\n|a\u03b2\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) possessing\n|a\u03b2\u00fata\n|(was) possessed\n|}\n== Relation to written Latin ==\nContrary to the traditional view, Wright argues that there was no distinction between Latin and Romance prior to the ninth century in France, the former being only a written representation of the latter. For instance in ninth-century Spain \u27e8saeculum\u27e9 was simply the correct way to spell [sjeglo], meaning 'century'. The writer would not have actually said [s\u025bkulum] any more than a modern English speaker would pronounce \u27e8knight\u27e9 as *[kn\u026axt].<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 44\u201350</ref> \n\n[[Ecclesiastical Latin]], in its spoken form, was created later during the [[Carolingian Renaissance]]. The British scholar [[Alcuin]], tasked by [[Charlemagne]] with improving the standards of Latin writing in France, prescribed a pronunciation based on a fairly literal interpretation of Latin spelling. A word such as \u27e8viridiarium\u27e9 'orchard' now had to be read aloud precisely as it was spelled rather than as [[Old French]] ''vergier.''<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 104\u20137</ref>\n\nThis had the effect of rendering [[Sermon|sermons]] completely unintelligible to the general public, which prompted officials a few years later- at the [[Council of Tours]]- to order them to be rendered ''in rusticam romanam linguam'', 'in plain roman speech', i.e. in Romance.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 118-20</ref> Another issue was that now two types of speech, Romance and Church Latin, had to coexist within one writing system. Within the same century the first attempts were made to devise an orthography specifically for Romance, as can be seen in the [[Oaths of Strasbourg]] and the [[Sequence of Saint Eulalia|Canticle of Saint Eulalia]], both written in France. As the Carolingian Reforms spread to other Romance-speaking areas, local scholars devised orthographies for their own varieties of Romance as well.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 122\u201332, 143\u20134</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-lg}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=2014-11-14|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|editor2-last=Schweickard|editor2-first=Wolfgang|editor3-last=Gouvert|editor3-first=Joannes|editor4-last=Kramer|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110313482|journal=Beihefte zur Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=|pages=295|doi=10.1515/9783110313482|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/963581913|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom) 2|date=2016|publisher=De Gruyter|year=2016|isbn=3-11-045361-4|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|location=|pages=|oclc=963581913|editor-last2=Gouvert|editor-first2=Xavier}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Loporcaro|first=Michele|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1107082342|title=Vowel Length From Latin to Romance|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-965655-4|location=|pages=25-30|oclc=1107082342}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Dworkin|first=Steven N.|date=2016-01-01|title=Do Romanists need to reconstruct Proto-Romance?|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/zrp-2016-0001|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=132|issue=1|pages=2|doi=10.1515/zrp-2016-0001|issn=1865-9063|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Ferguson|first=Thaddeus|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110806960|title=A History of the Romance Vowel Systems through Paradigmatic Reconstruction|date=1976-01-31|publisher=De Gruyter|year=|isbn=978-3-11-080696-0|location=Berlin, Boston|pages=78}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Wilkinson, Hugh E.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1055897845|title=Notes on the development of -KJ-, -TJ- in Spanish and Portuguese|date=1926|publisher=Aoyama Gakuin University|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=11-14|oclc=1055897845}}\n* {{Citation|last=Zampaulo|first=Andr\u00e9|title=Palatal Sound Change in the Romance languages|date=2019-08-22|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780198807384.003.0006|work=Palatal Sound Change in the Romance Languages|volume=|pages=150\u2013199|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-880738-4|access-date=2020-04-01}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=R.|last2=Gaeng|first2=P. A.|date=1992|title=La Declinaison Nominale du Latin Non Classique: Essai d'une Methode de Synthese|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|journal=Probus|volume=4|issue=2|pages=|doi=10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|issn=0921-4771|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert Anderson, 1911-|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/422266905|title=Proto-Romance phonology|date=1976|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=0-444-00183-2|oclc=422266905}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert A. (Robert Anderson), 1911-1997.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/10773070|title=Proto-Romance Morphology|date=1983|publisher=John Benjamins Pub. Co|year=|isbn=90-272-3522-8|location=|pages=|oclc=10773070}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=Robert|last2=W\u00fcest|first2=Jakob|date=1993|title=Les syst\u00e8mes casuels du prototoman|url=https://elibrary.narr.digital/article/99.125005/vox199310025|journal=Vox Romanica|volume=52|issue=1|pages=25-65|issn=0042-899X|via=eLibrary}}\n*Alkire, Ti; Rosen, Rosen (July 2010). ''Romance Languages: A Historical Introduction''. New York: Cambridge University Press. ISBN <bdi>9780521717847</bdi>.\n*{{Cite book|last=Vincent|first=Nigel|title=Early and Late Latin: Continuity or Change?|last2=Adams|first2=J. N.|last3=Maltby|first3=Robert|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-107-13225-2|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Wright|first=Roger|title=Late Latin and Early Romance in Spain and Carolingian France|publisher=Francis Cairns|year=1982|isbn=0-905205-12-X|location=Liverpool|pages=}}\n[[Category:Latin]]\n[[Category:Linguistics]]\n", "text_old": "'''Proto-Romance''' is the [[Comparative method|comparatively]] [[Linguistic reconstruction|reconstructed]] ancestor of all [[Romance languages|Romance Languages]]. It reflects a late variety of [[Latin]], one of the [[Italic languages|Italic Languages]] in the broader [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] family.\n\nExceptionally in the field of [[Comparative linguistics|Comparative Linguistics]], specialists in Proto-Romance have at their disposal an abundant corpus of their [[Proto-language|proto language]] in its written register- that is to say, Latin. This has however had the drawback of leading many scholars to rely excessively on the written record in lieu of reconstructing Proto-Romance proper.<ref>Dworkin (2016), p. 2</ref> \n\nAs conceived in the Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman, Proto-Romance most closely reflects Latin as spoken around the sixth century AD.<ref>Kramer (2014), p. 295</ref>\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Monophthongs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|Close]]\n|{{IPA link|i}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|u}}\n|-\n![[Near-close vowel|Near-close]]\n|[[Near-close near-front unrounded vowel|\u026a]]\n|\n|[[Near-close back rounded vowel|\u028a]]\n|-\n![[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|e}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|o}}\n|-\n![[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|\u025b}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u0254}}\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Open]]\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u00e4|a}}\n|\n|}\n\n* The open-mid vowels /\u025b, \u0254/ merge with /e, o/ in all unstressed contexts.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 73\u20136</ref><ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 78</ref>\n\n* A further reduction is observed in intertonic syllables where /i, u/ merge with /\u026a, \u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 78\u201381</ref>\n\n* Vowels are lengthened allophonically in stressed open syllables,<ref>Loporcaro (2015), pp. 25\u201330</ref> although not /\u026a/ or /\u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 69</ref>\n\n* /i, u/ become [j, w] between a consonant and following vowel. [j] then triggers [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalization]], e.g. /basi\u00e1re/ [bas\u02b2\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref>\n\n=== Diphthong ===\nOnly one diphthong can be reconstructed for Proto-Romance, namely /aw/. It can be found in both stressed and unstressed positions.<ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 84</ref> Its phonemic status is however debatable, as it could also be simply regarded as a sequence of /a/ and /u/.<ref>Xavier, p. 81</ref>\n\n=== Consonants ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Labial\n! colspan=\"2\" |Coronal\n! colspan=\"2\" |Velar\n! colspan=\"2\" |Palatal\n|-\n!Nasal\n|\n|m\n|\n|n\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Occlusive\n|p\n|b\n|t\n|d\n|k\n|g\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |j\n|-\n!Fricative\n|f\n|\u03b2\n|s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Labialized\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|k\u02b7\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Vibrant\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |r\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Lateral\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |l\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n* When palatalized /t, k, n, l/ become [ts\u02b2, c, \u0272, \u028e].<ref name=\"Xavier\" /><ref>Zampaulo (2019), pp. 50, 78, 94</ref>\n* Intervocalic [c, \u0272, \u028e] regularly [[Gemination|geminate]].<ref name=\"Xavier\">Xavier (2014), pp. 92\u2013115</ref> [ts\u02b2] does so only sporadically.<ref>Wilkin (1926), pp. 11\u201314</ref>\n*Words beginning with /sC/ undergo [[Prothesis (linguistics)|prosthesis]], e.g. /st\u00e1re/ [\u026ast\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee], unless preceded by a vowel.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 125\u20136</ref><ref>Hall (1976), p. 128</ref>\n* It is debated whether /k\u02b7/ is its own phoneme or merely an allophone of /ku/ before vowels.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 100</ref>\n* There is some evidence that /f/ could have been bilabial, but a labiodental is still more likely.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 38</ref>\n* /b, d, g/ fricativize to [\u03b2, \u00f0, \u0263] between vowels or in contact with /r/ and /l/.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 48</ref>\n* Intervocalic /di, gi/ do not occur, these having previously reduced to /j/.<ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 87</ref><ref>Xavier (2016), p. 43</ref>\n*The rhotic may have been [\u027e~r], as in Spanish or Catalan.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 113</ref>\n*Word-initial /j/ underwent fortition to [\u025f].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 84</ref>\n* /ll/ had a retroflex realization: [\u026d\u026d].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 115</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 164</ref>\n* /gn/ fricativizes to [\u0263n].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 95</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 80</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n\n=== Nouns ===\nProto-Romance nouns had three cases: [[Nominative case|nominative]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], and a combined [[Genitive case|genitive]]-[[Dative case|dative]] which was only used in reference to humans.<ref>De Dardel & Gaenge (1992), p. 104</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Class\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"2\" |f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028e\u028as\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028ei\n|m\u00e1tr\u026as''{{efn|De Dardel hesitates to posit this form, giving ''m\u00e1tre'' as a possible alternative. Likewise ''p\u00e1tr\u026as~p\u00e1tre''.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tr\u026as\n|p\u00e1tri\n|-\n!Accusative\n|f\u00e9m\u026anas\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eu''{{efn|For final -u versus -\u028as, see Xavier (2014), p. 78.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eos\n|m\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tres\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|fem\u026an\u00f3ru''{{efn|Unlike De Dardel, Hall (1976, p. 18) has -''aru'' as the feminine ending, as it was in Classical Latin. On the next page, however, he admits that the evidence for it is flimsy.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eo\n|fi\u028e\u028e\u00f3ru\n|m\u00e1tri\n|matr\u00f3ru\n|p\u00e1tri\n|patr\u00f3ru\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |woman\n| colspan=\"2\" |son\n| colspan=\"2\" |mother\n| colspan=\"2\" |father\n|}\n\nSeveral Class III nouns had inflections that differed by syllable count or stress position.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 28</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |singular\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u0254\u0301mo\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|p\u00e1stor\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|s\u0254\u0301ror\n|-\n!Accusative\n|\u0254\u0301m\u026ane\n|past\u00f3re\n|sor\u00f3re\n|-\n!Translation\n|man\n|pastor\n|sister\n|}\nA few Class II nouns were pluralized with -''a'' or ''-ora,'' these originally having been neuter in Classical Latin. Though their singular was masculine, the plural was treated as feminine.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 23\u20134, 29\u201330.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Noun''{{efn|Forms given in the accusative.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2u\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2a\n|braccu\n|bracca\n|t\u025b\u0301mp\u028as\n|t\u025b\u0301mpora\n|p\u025b\u0301kt\u028as\n|p\u025b\u0301ktora\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |egg\n| colspan=\"2\" |arm\n| colspan=\"2\" |time\n| colspan=\"2\" |chest\n|}\nThe plural was often reanalyzed as a feminine singular, resulting in gender shifts.<ref>Akire & Rosen (2010), pp. 193\u20134</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Original noun\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eu\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nu\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|-\n!Fem. variant\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eas\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nas\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |leaf\n| colspan=\"2\" |firewood\n|}\nSuch a trend had already begun in Classical Latin; for example the feminine noun ''opera'' was formed from the plural of neuter ''opus.''\n\n=== Adjectives ===\n\n==== Absolute ====\nBroadly speaking, these decline as nouns do.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Gender\n| colspan=\"2\" |feminine\n| colspan=\"2\" |masculine\n| colspan=\"2\" |either\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"2\" |bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bl\u00e1nd\u028as\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|d\u028a\u0301lk\u026as\n| rowspan=\"2\" |d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Accusative\n|bl\u00e1ndas\n|bl\u00e1ndu\n|bl\u00e1ndos\n|d\u028a\u0301lke\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|d\u028a\u0301lki\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |sweet\n|}\n\n==== Comparative ====\nWhile the original Latin ending ''-(i)or'' still existed, it was only used in a limited number of adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 32, 119-20</ref><ref>Maltby (2016), p. 340</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|m\u025b\u0301\u028e\u028eor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|p\u025b\u0301jor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |pej\u00f3res\n|m\u00e1jor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026a\u0301nor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Accusative\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3re\n|pej\u00f3re\n|maj\u00f3re\n|m\u026an\u00f3re\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3ri\n| -\n|pej\u00f3ri\n| -\n|maj\u00f3ri\n|  -\n|m\u026an\u00f3ri\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |better\n| colspan=\"2\" |worse\n| colspan=\"2\" |larger\n| colspan=\"2\" |smaller\n|}\nThe typical way to form a comparative was to add either ''pl\u00fas'' or ''m\u00e1is'' (meaning 'more') to an absolute adjective, which had been done sporadically in Classical Latin as well.<ref>Maltby (2016), pp. 340\u20135.</ref>\n\n==== Superlative ====\nNo dedicated ending existed to express the superlative. A variety of alternatives were used instead, such as an intensifying adverb (m\u028a\u0301ltu, b\u025b\u0301ne, etc.) or a comparative.<ref>Bauer (2016), pp. 340, 359</ref>\n\n==== Possessive ====\n\nShown here in the feminine singular.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 122</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!\n!First person\n!Second person\n!Third person\n|-\n!singular\n|m\u025b\u0301a\n|t\u028a\u0301a\n|s\u028a\u0301a\n|-\n!plural\n|n\u0254\u0301stra\n|\u03b2\u0254\u0301stra\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|}\n\n=== Pronouns ===\n\n==== Personal ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'you', 'me', etc.<ref>De Dardel & W\u00fcest (1993), p. 43</ref><ref name=\"Hall\">Hall (1983), p. 39</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Person\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u025b\u0301o''{{efn|On the cited page, Hall has this as ''ego''. However ''eo'' is found in Hall (1976), p. 216|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |n\u00f3s\n|t\u00fa\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\u03b2\u00f3s\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301lle\n| colspan=\"2\" |\u026a\u0301lli\n|-\n!Accusative\n|m\u00e9, m\u00e9ne\n|t\u00e9, t\u00e9ne\n|\u026a\u0301llas\n|\u026a\u0301llu\n|\u026a\u0301llos\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|m\u00ed, m\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|n\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|t\u00ed, t\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|\u03b2\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|\u026all\u00e9i\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|\u026all\u00fai\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|}\n\n==== Interrogative ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'who' and 'what'.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 42\u201343</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Animacy\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Animate\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Inanimate\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| colspan=\"2\" |ku\u00ed\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u026a\u0301d\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Accusative\n|ku\u025b\u0301ne\n|ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\n\nProto Romance verbs belong to three main classes, each of which is characterized by a different [[thematic vowel]]. Their conjugations are built on three stems and involve various combinations of mood, aspect, and tense.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 47\u201350</ref> Only one chart is shown below; the rest will be explained in a separate article.\n\n==== Present indicative ====\nThis could also connote the near future.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 52\u20136</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |First person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Third person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Translation\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Class I\n|k\u00e1nto\n|kant\u00e1m\u028as\n|k\u00e1ntas\n|kant\u00e1t\u026as\n|k\u00e1ntat\n|k\u00e1ntant\n|sing\n|-\n!Class II\n|d\u0254\u0301rmo\n|dorm\u00edm\u028as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026as\n|d\u0254rm\u00edt\u026as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026at\n|d\u0254\u0301rment<br>~d\u0254\u0301rm\u028ant\n|sleep\n|-\n!Class III\n|b\u00e1tto\n|batt\u00e9m\u028as\n|b\u00e1ttes\n|batt\u00e9t\u026as\n|b\u00e1ttet\n|b\u00e1ttent\n|beat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Irregular\n|s\u028a\u0301n\n|s\u028a\u0301m\u028as\n|\u025b\u0301s\n|\u025b\u0301st\u026as~s\u025b\u0301t\u026as~s\u028a\u0301t\u026as\n|\u025b\u0301st\n|s\u028a\u0301nt\n|am/are/is\n|-\n|\u00e1jo\n|a\u03b2\u00e9m\u028as\n|\u00e1s\n|a\u03b2\u00e9t\u026as\n|\u00e1t\n|\u00e1nt~\u00e1unt\n|have/has\n|}\n\n==== Participles ====\nOf these there were only two: a present active and a preterite passive. They declined like adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 122\u20133</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Present Active\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Preterite Passive\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n|-\n!Class I\n|am\u00e1nte\n|(is) adoring\n|am\u00e1ta\n|(was) adored\n|-\n!Class II\n|fin\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) finishing\n|fin\u00edta\n|(was) finished\n|-\n!Class III\n|a\u03b2\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) possessing\n|a\u03b2\u00fata\n|(was) possessed\n|}\n== Relation to written Latin ==\nContrary to the traditional view, Wright argues that there was no distinction between Latin and Romance prior to the ninth century in France, the former being only a written representation of the latter. For instance in ninth-century Spain \u27e8saeculum\u27e9 was simply the correct way to spell [sjeglo], meaning 'century'. The writer would not have actually said [s\u025bkulum] any more than a modern English speaker would pronounce \u27e8knight\u27e9 as *[kn\u026axt].<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 44\u201350</ref> \n\n[[Ecclesiastical Latin]], in its spoken form, was created later during the [[Carolingian Renaissance]]. The British scholar [[Alcuin]], tasked by [[Charlemagne]] with improving the standards of Latin writing in France, prescribed a pronunciation based on a fairly literal interpretation of Latin spelling. A word such as \u27e8viridiarium\u27e9 'orchard' now had to be read aloud precisely as it was spelled rather than as [[Old French]] ''vergier.''<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 104\u20137</ref>\n\nThis had the effect of rendering [[Sermon|sermons]] completely unintelligible to the general public, which prompted officials a few years later- at the [[Council of Tours]]- to order them to be rendered ''in rusticam romanam linguam'', 'in plain roman speech', i.e. in Romance.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 118-20</ref> Another issue was that now two types of speech, Romance and Church Latin, had to coexist within one writing system. Within the same century the first attempts were made to devise an orthography specifically for Romance, as can be seen in the [[Oaths of Strasbourg]] and the [[Sequence of Saint Eulalia|Canticle of Saint Eulalia]], both written in France. As the Carolingian Reforms spread to other Romance-speaking areas, local scholars devised orthographies for their own varieties of Romance as well.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 122\u201332, 143\u20134</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-lg}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=2014-11-14|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|editor2-last=Schweickard|editor2-first=Wolfgang|editor3-last=Gouvert|editor3-first=Joannes|editor4-last=Kramer|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110313482|journal=Beihefte zur Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=|pages=295|doi=10.1515/9783110313482|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http:/