rary was founded in the village of Georgiaville in 1872 by the Bernon Manufacturing Company. It closed after about ten years, but was reopened in 1903 through the cooperation of interested citizens and the Manville-Jenckes Company. It eventually moved to the gallery of a former Baptist Church, and in 1919 it moved again to a refurbished grocery store. \n\nThe Esmond Library was established in 1916, when Esmond Mills contributed space and funding for a library. Esmond Mills closed in 1946 due to labor troubles, and the library closed along with it. Numerous books were destroyed when water pipes burst in the abandoned building. The Rhode Island-based conglomerate Textron eventually acquired the building, and after considerable time and effort the Smithfield Recreational Association persuaded Textron to deed the building to the town for recreational purposes. The Smithfield Recreational Association rejuvenated the library, and Elodie Blackmore was appointed librarian in 1954. She catalogued and prepared approximately 2,500 books for circulation. Today, the library's collection totals approximately 70,000 books.\n\nThe East Smithfield Public Library was born in 1967, when the boards of the Bernon and Esmond libraries decided to consolidate. Bernon Library was designated as a reading center, and one librarian managed both buildings. Sadly, in 1973, budget cuts forced the decision to close the Bernon reading center and transfer its collection to the East Smithfield Public Library.\n\nIn 1982, the library was asked to submit a proposal to the Town Council on the feasibility of renovating and utilizing part of the former Dorothy T.P. Dame School as a possible solution to the overcrowding that came as a result of combining both libraries. The Board of Trustees and library staff jumped at the opportunity to secure almost three times more operating space. The Town Council granted the use of the first floor to the library in August 1982, and finally, in 1985, after a tremendous volunteer effort by the entire Smithfield community, the contents of the library were moved to its present location at 50 Esmond Street.\n\nDuring the past 25 years - with help from the [[Champlin Foundations]] and the [[Smithfield, Rhode Island|Town of Smithfield]] - the library has renovated the second floor to provide much needed space for a computer area, media room and storage space, conference room, administration offices, and technical services work area. The library continues to thrive and serve the greater Smithfield community with services and resources for all ages.<ref>http://www.eastsmithfieldpubliclibrary.org|Library's{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} website</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Greenville Public Library (Rhode Island)]]\n*[[List of libraries in Rhode Island]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.eastsmithfieldpubliclibrary.org|Library's website}}\n*[http://sites.google.com/site/esmyap Young Adult Page]\n\n[[Category:Public libraries in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Education in Providence County, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Smithfield, Rhode Island]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Smithfield_Public_Library"}
{"title_page": "East Orange Public Library", "text_new": "The '''East Orange Public Library''' is the free [[public library]] of [[East Orange, New Jersey|East Orange]], [[Essex County, New Jersey]]\n\n==Locations and circulation==\nAs of 2011, the library had a collection of 343,918 volumes, served a population of approximately 73,000 and circulated 318,748 items annually.<ref name = librarytech>{{Cite web   | title = East Orange Public Library   | work =    | publisher = librarytechnology.org   | date = September 2011   | url = http://www.librarytechnology.org/libraries.pl?Institution=East%20Orange,%20NJ   | accessdate = 2011-09-29}}</ref> from four locations.<ref name = eopl>[http://www.eopl.org/ East Orange Public Library]</ref>\n\n*Main Library - 21 South Arlington Avenue\n*Ampere Branch - Ampere Plaza\n*Elmwood Branch - 317 South Clinton Street\n*Franklin Branch - 192 Dodd Street\n\n==Carnegie libraries==\nOf the library's four locations, two were originally among the [[List of Carnegie libraries in New Jersey|thirty-six Carnegie-funded libraries in New Jersey]]. East Orange's original library buildings, except the Ampere Branch, were constructed in part with funds from the $116,000 in grants from the [[Carnegie Corporation of New York|Carnegie Corporation]].<ref name= bobinski>{{cite book|last=Bobinski|first=George S.|title=Carnegie Libraries: Their History and Impact on American Public Library Development|publisher=American Library Association|location=Chicago|year=1969|isbn=0-8389-0022-4|ref=Bobinski}}</ref><ref name = jones>{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Theodore|title=Carnegie Libraries Across America|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=New York|year=1997|isbn=0-471-14422-3|ref=Jones}}</ref> The former Main Branch, now a courthouse, was also a [[Carnegie library]].<ref name = vintage>{{Citation   | last = Hart    | first = Bill   | author-link =    | title = East Orange in Vinage Postcards   | publisher = Arcadia Publishing   | year = 2000   | volume =    | edition =    | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9SsrumYZXQ0C&pg=PA28 | isbn = 978-0-7385-0457-5   | quote = }}</ref>\n\n===East Orange Municipal Court Building===\nThe first of libraries built with Carnegie funding was the former Main Library. Alexander King, resident of the city and child-hood friend of [[Andrew Carnegie]], orchestrated the first grant to be offered in New Jersey made January 18, 1900.<ref name= bobinski/><ref name = jones/><ref name = vintage/> Originally it was of source of controversy. While Carnegie offered $50,000 he also stipulated $5,000 be committed by the municipality for its upkeep, and some residents felt they would prefer to manage the city's library without Carnegie's interference and could easily make use of the recently opened [[Orange Public Library|library in Orange]].<ref>{{Cite news  | title = Oppose a Carnegie Library; Some Residents of East Orange Will Fight the Acceptance of the Millionaire's Offer. | newspaper = The New York Times   | date = January 22, 1900   | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10612F63A5811738DDDAB0A94D9405B808CF1D3 | accessdate = 2011-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Oppose Carnegie Library Residents of East Orange will Fight Offer| newspaper = Meriden Morning Record   | date = January 23, 1900\n|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2513&dat=19000123&id=3Wk1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=2RMLAAAAIBAJ&pg=1041,309588| accessdate = 2011-10-03}}</ref>\nEventually the city purchased a lot a Main Street and South Munn Avenue where the building was constructed and opened on January 3, 1903.<ref name = vintage/> This original section was the work [[Albert Randolph Ross|Ackerman and Ross]], who also designed the library that is now houses the [[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Library History |publisher=Port Jervis Free Public Library |url=http://www.portjervislibrary.org/portjervis/about.asp |accessdate=2011-10-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914113020/http://www.portjervislibrary.org/portjervis/about.asp |archivedate=2011-09-14 }}</ref> In 1914, the Carnegie Library Fund granted another $40,000 to an expansion of much needed wings, designed by Hobart A. Walker and opened the following year.<ref name = vintage/>\nCirca 1974, the building was altered and converted to the East Orange Municipal Court and later renovated again in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web   | title = 1903-2009 Then and Now The East Orange Library   | work = East Orange Timeline   | publisher =    | year = 2009   | url = http://eohistory.info/EOTimeLine/1903-2009.htm   | accessdate = 2011-10-04   | quote = }}</ref>\n\n===Franklin Branch Library===\nAfter receiving a grant of $13,000, the Franklin Branch was built, opening on August 1, 1909 at its location on Dodd Street near [[Watsessing Park]]. It was expanded in 1939.<ref name = vintage/>\n\n===Elmwood Branch Library===\nThe Elmwood Branch was made possible through a $13,000 grant from the Carnegie Library Fund and opened on January 12, 1912.<ref name = vintage/>\n\n==Ampere Branch==\nThe Ampere Branch opened as a deposit station in 1915. After changing locations it became a branch library in 1923, and on March 17, 1931 moved to its current location<ref name=vintage/> across from the former [[Ampere (NJT station)|Ampere Station]]. The building was originally built around 1914 as horse-drawn fire engine station; a second floor was added in the 1950s, and underwent renovation in 2010.<ref>{{Citation   | last = Bondy   | first = Halley   | author-link =    | title = East Orange library closed for asbsestos should reopen by summer   | newspaper = The Star-Ledger   | date = March 24, 2010   | url = http://www.nj.com/news/local/index.ssf/2010/03/east_orange_library_closed_for.html   | accessdate =}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Carnegie libraries in New Jersey]]\n*[[Newark Public Library]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Essex County, New Jersey]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.eopl.org/ East Orange Public Library]\n* [http://www.nd.edu/~archlib/Carnegie/full/42.jpg Floor plan of Main Library 1903]\n* [http://eohistory.info/EOTimeLine/1903-2009.htm 1903-2009 Then and Now The East Orange Library]\n\n{{coord|40.760003|-74.211725|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NJ|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:East Orange, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1903]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1915]]\n[[Category:Carnegie libraries in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Education in Essex County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Essex County, New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "The '''East Orange Public Library''' is the free [[public library]] of [[East Orange, New Jersey|East Orange]], [[Essex County, New Jersey]]\n\n==Locations and circulation==\nAs of 2011, the library had a collection of 343,918 volumes, served a population of approximately 73,000 and circulated 318,748 items annually.<ref name = librarytech>{{Cite web   | title = East Orange Public Library   | work =    | publisher = librarytechnology.org   | date = September 2011   | url = http://www.librarytechnology.org/libraries.pl?Institution=East%20Orange,%20NJ   | accessdate = 2011-09-29}}</ref> from four locations.<ref name = eopl>[http://www.eopl.org/ East Orange Public Library]</ref>\n\n*Main Library - 21 South Arlington Avenue\n*Ampere Branch - Ampere Plaza\n*Elmwood Branch - 317 South Clinton Street\n*Franklin Branch - 192 Dodd Street\n\n==Carnegie libraries==\nOf the library's four locations, two were originally among the [[List of Carnegie libraries in New Jersey|thirty-six Carnegie-funded libraries in New Jersey]]. East Orange's original library buildings, except the Ampere Branch, were constructed in part with funds from the $116,000 in grants from the [[Carnegie Corporation of New York|Carnegie Corporation]].<ref n