 = January 23, 1900\n|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2513&dat=19000123&id=3Wk1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=2RMLAAAAIBAJ&pg=1041,309588| accessdate = 2011-10-03}}</ref>\nEventually the city purchased a lot a Main Street and South Munn Avenue where the building was constructed and opened on January 3, 1903.<ref name = vintage/> This original section was the work [[Albert Randolph Ross|Ackerman and Ross]], who also designed the library that is now houses the [[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Library History |publisher=Port Jervis Free Public Library |url=http://www.portjervislibrary.org/portjervis/about.asp |accessdate=2011-10-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914113020/http://www.portjervislibrary.org/portjervis/about.asp |archivedate=2011-09-14 }}</ref> In 1914, the Carnegie Library Fund granted another $40,000 to an expansion of much needed wings, designed by Hobart A. Walker and opened the following year.<ref name = vintage/>\nCirca 1974, the building was altered and converted to the East Orange Municipal Court and later renovated again in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web   | title = 1903-2009 Then and Now The East Orange Library   | work = East Orange Timeline   | publisher =    | year = 2009   | url = http://eohistory.info/EOTimeLine/1903-2009.htm   | accessdate = 2011-10-04   | quote = }}</ref>\n\n===Franklin Branch Library===\nAfter receiving a grant of $13,000, the Franklin Branch was built, opening on August 1, 1909 at its location on Dodd Street near [[Watsessing Park]]. It was expanded in 1939.<ref name = vintage/>\n\n===Elmwood Branch Library===\nThe Elmwood Branch was made possible through a $13,000 grant from the Carnegie Library Fund and opened on January 12, 1912.<ref name = vintage/>\n\n==Ampere Branch==\nThe Ampere Branch opened as a deposit station in 1915. After changing locations it became a branch library in 1923, and on March 17, 1931 moved to its current location<ref name=vintage/> across from the former [[Ampere (NJT station)|Ampere Station]]. The building was originally built around 1914 as horse-drawn fire engine station; a second floor was added in the 1950s, and underwent renovation in 2010.<ref>{{Citation   | last = Bondy   | first = Halley   | author-link =    | title = East Orange library closed for asbsestos should reopen by summer   | newspaper = The Star-Ledger   | date = March 24, 2010   | url = http://www.nj.com/news/local/index.ssf/2010/03/east_orange_library_closed_for.html   | accessdate =}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Carnegie libraries in New Jersey]]\n*[[Newark Public Library]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Essex County, New Jersey]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.eopl.org/ East Orange Public Library]\n* [http://www.nd.edu/~archlib/Carnegie/full/42.jpg Floor plan of Main Library 1903]\n* [http://eohistory.info/EOTimeLine/1903-2009.htm 1903-2009 Then and Now The East Orange Library]\n\n{{coord|40.760003|-74.211725|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NJ|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:East Orange, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1903]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1915]]\n[[Category:Carnegie libraries in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Education in Essex County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Essex County, New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Orange_Public_Library"}
{"title_page": "Rahul Kaswan", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox Indian politician\n| name        = Rahul Kaswan\n| image       = RAHUL JI KASWAN MP.jpg\n| caption     =Rahul Kaswan in 2014 \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_place = [[Rajgarh, Rajasthan|Rajgarh]], [[Rajasthan]], [[India]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1977|01|20|df=yes}}\n| residence   = Deep Niwas [[Sadulpur]] \n| religion    = [[Hindu]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament]], [[Lok Sabha]]\n|term_start   = 16 May 2014\n|term_end     =\n| constituency = [[Churu (Lok Sabha constituency)|Churu]]\n|spouse = Neelu Kaswan (m. 2000)\n| predecessor  = [[Ram Singh Kaswan]]\n| parents = [[Ram Singh Kaswan]] (Father)<br>Kamla Kaswan (Mother)\n| party        = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| education  = B. Com, PGDM ([[Delhi University]]) and (National Institute of Sales, Delhi)\n| nationality = [[India|Indian]]\n}}\n\n'''Rahul Kaswan''' is an Indian politician who was member of [[16th Lok Sabha|Sixteenth Lok Sabha]] from [[Churu (Lok Sabha constituency)|Churu]] parliamentary constituency as BJP candidate, defeating Abhinesh Maharshi (BSP) by a margin of 294,739 votes. He is the youngest MP from Rajasthan.\n\nThe 37-year-old MP won with a record margin of 294,739 votes, the highest ever in the Churu constituency, thereby getting the rank of 6th highest margin winner, out of 25 seats in [[Rajasthan]]. He was pitted against Congress' first-timer Pratap Punia in the Churu Lok Sabha constituency. He is the son of Shri [[Ram Singh Kaswan]], party's sitting MP from [[Churu district|Churu]], Rajasthan. The senior Kaswan has been the Churu MP for four terms. His mother Kamala Kaswan too has been a legislator from the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eciresults.nic.in/ConstituencywiseS203.htm?ac=3 |title=Constituencywise-All Candidates |publisher=Eciresults.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2014-05-17}}</ref><ref>http://india.gov.in/my-government/indian-parliament/rahul-kaswan</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{16th LS members from Rajasthan |state=expanded}}\n{{17th LS members from Rajasthan}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaswan, Rahul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:16th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:People from Churu district]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:17th Lok Sabha members]]\n\n\n{{Rajasthan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox Indian politician\n| name        = Rahul Kaswan\n| image       = RAHUL JI KASWAN MP.jpg\n| caption     =Rahul Kaswan in 2014 \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_place = [[Rajgarh, Rajasthan|Rajgarh]], [[Rajasthan]], [[India]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1977|01|20|df=yes}}\n| residence   = Deep Niwas [[Sadulpur]] \n| religion    = [[Hindu]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament]], [[Lok Sabha]]\n|term_start   = 16 May 2014\n|term_end     =\n| constituency = [[Churu (Lok Sabha constituency)|Churu]]\n|spouse = Neelu Kaswan (m. 2000)\n| predecessor  = [[Ram Singh Kaswan]]\n| parents = [[Ram Singh Kaswan]] (Father)<br>Kamla Kaswan (Mother)\n| party        = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| education  = B. Com, PGDM ([[Delhi University]]) and (National Institute of Sales, Delhi)\n| nationality = [[India|Indian]]\n}}\n\n'''Rahul Kaswan''' is an Indian politician who was member of [[16th Lok Sabha|Sixteenth Lok Sabha]] from [[Churu (Lok Sabha constituency)|Churu]] parliamentary constituency as BJP candidate, defeating Abhinesh Maharshi (BSP) by a margin of 294,739 votes. He is the youngest MP from Rajasthan.\n\nThe 37-year-old MP won with a record margin of 294,739 votes, the highest ever in the Churu constituency, thereby getting the rank of 6th highest margin winner, out of 25 seats in [[Rajasthan]]. He was pitted against Congress' first-timer Pratap Punia in the Churu Lok Sabha constituency. He is the son of Shri [[Ram Singh Kaswan]], party's sitting MP from [[Churu]], Rajasthan. The senior Kaswan has been the Churu MP for four terms. His mother Kamala Kaswan too has been a legislator from the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eciresults.nic.in/ConstituencywiseS203.htm?ac=3 |title=Constituencywise-All Candidates |publisher=Eciresults.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2014-05-17}}</ref><ref>http://india.gov.in/my-government/indian-parliament/rahul-kaswan</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{16th LS members from Rajasthan |state=expanded}}\n{{17th LS members from Rajasthan}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaswan, Rahul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:16th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:People from Churu district]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:17th Lok Sabha members]]\n\n\n{{Rajasthan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahul_Kaswan"}
{"title_page": "Dyer Library", "text_new": "{{Coord|43.501|-70.4416|display=title}}\n{{ infobox library\n| image              = Dyer_Library.jpg\n| library_name       = Dyer Library\n| country            = United States\n| type               = Public\n| established        = 1881\n| location           = [[Saco, Maine]]\n| collection_size    = 53,000\n| annual_circulation = 168,000\n| pop_served         = 18,482\n| budget             = $440,016\n| director           = Leslie Rounds \n| num_employees      = 15\n| website            = {{URL|http://www.dyerlibrarysacomuseum.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Dyer Library''' is the [[public library]] serving [[Saco, Maine]].<ref>{{cite web |title=A Maine Public Library: Dyer Library |url=https://www.maine.gov/msl/libs/directories/displaypub.shtml?id=40938 |website=Maine.gov |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nFunded by a bequest from Olive Dyer, the first home of the Dyer Library opened in 1881 in the basement of Saco City Hall.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dyer Library Archives/Saco Museum Facts |url=http://dyersaco.mainememory.net/page/2664/display.html |website=Dyer Library Archives/Saco Museum - Maine Memory Network |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Breeding |first1=Marshall |title=Dyer Library -- Saco, ME |url=https://librarytechnology.org/library/19334 |website=libraries.org |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The library is now located in the [[J.G. Deering House]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wells |first1=Tammy |title=Dyer Library seeks community help for cornice repairs |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2019/11/01/dyer-library-seeks-community-help-for-cornice-repairs/ |accessdate=20 December 2019 |work=[[Portland Press Herald]] |date=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.dyerlibrarysacomuseum.org/lib_home.shtml}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Public libraries in Maine]]\n[[Category:1881 establishments in Maine]]\n[[Category:Libraries es